name: The Cottage, Rath, Baltimore, West Cork
description: Lovely well-equipped 2 bedroom cottage available for visiting beautiful Baltimore & West Cork!  3kms from the village & on the main road for easy finding.  Stunning setting beside the estuary, near Carbery's Hundred Isles, and plenty of parking. Cleaning included in price, so no extra fees.
neighborhood_overview:
The cottage is located in the small hamlet of Rath, 3kms from Baltimore village. It is directly on the main road to Baltimore. Round the corner (10 minutes walk) are the church, the Sibin pub (which serves food and has music at the weekend) and the school.
We are on the estuary of a 100 isles so there are beautiful views around the locale and it is classified as an area of outstanding natural beauty.
3kms down the road and you have the village of Baltimore, with a shop (with atm), pubs, restaurants, sailing clubs, water sports, swimming pool and a playground. Also
6kms away is the famous Lough Hyne (recently listed in the Irish Times 20 Best Places to go wild in Ireland for walking, swimming and diving).
8kms away is Skibbereen, the main town for this part of West Cork with banks, post office, a Lidl, , arts centre, medical centre and everything else.
host_about:
I'm a laid back librarian who enjoys sports and loves animals. 
Have 20 years experience in the property sector, both as a tenant and landlord, and also have happened to work in an architecture library! 
I love making places as homely, comfortable and welcoming as possible as I know the inconvenience of a noisy pipe or an awkward plug! 
(I also enjoy gardening)
West Cork is the most amazing place in the world to live, scenery, sea and friendliness = fantastic!

name: Old Rectory Retreat Westport -  Olde KitchenHouse
description:
THE OLDE KITCHENHOUSE is one of two apartments at The Old Rectory Retreat. Quirky, beautiful and much loved, this is not a holiday rental place but a home we sometimes share with others. We offer atmosphere and the joy of age.

We are a small extended family group living around the Old Rectory - built in 1852 and set among trees, with a stream running between our gardens.

A house of 170 years age is not a blemish free space!

We're in Knappagh, 3 miles from beautiful Westport town.
neighborhood_overview: Westport is a Heritage Town situated in beautiful countryside on the shores of Clew Bay. It's one of Ireland’s few planned towns and a walk around town shows how beautifully designed it was. The town is always bustling with life but still keeps that small town feel that’s so relaxing in these often stressful times.The sea and the Holy Mountain are at our doorstep.The Greenway goes from Westport to Achill and has become beloved by cyclists and walkers. Our local area is full of beautiful walks and stories from history.There's a strong  community and people of all sorts including artistic, musical and sporty people are drawn here. What a lovely combination!
host_about:
I’m Róísín –  your hostess and general organiser. From the first time our family set eyes on The Old Rectory at Knappagh we knew we wanted to share it in some way with others…so this is a dream come true.  I’ve  written with and been involved in writers’ workshops on and off over the years and worked in amateur and community drama in one of many past lives. We feel our place offers a creative space in which people can work rest or just enjoy the surrounding area.
These days I have a new partner in my son Maitiú. Maitiú is 31 and has a business making cards from his art and words.  He helps keep the Tigín clean and tidy and welcomes guests.

name: Rural Retreat: Great location to explore the West
description:
Come and get away from it all!
The newly renovated cottage is located in Carracastle, Co. Mayo and is a perfect location to explore the West of Ireland due to our central location. Galway, Westport, Sligo and Carrick-on-Shannon are all within an hour’s drive.
Located on 30 acres of countryside with a beautiful river running though it.
We are only 15 mins from Knock airport by car.
neighborhood_overview: The cottage is located  a mile from the local village, which includes a church, a pub, a shop and a post office. There are beautiful views, walks and a peacefulness that simply restores.  There is access to fishing and horse riding nearby. Ballaghaderren is the local town and is 5 miles away with a range of shops, pubs, restaurants to explore. You will be a half an hour drive from Castlebar and 45 minutes to Sligo or Westport, Lough Key, Enniscrone. Day trips to Connemara and Achill are easily doable.
host_about:

We would love to  aid you in experiencing authentic rural Irish life.
 Whatever we can do to help we will, we are friendly,fun and easy going.
Come and enjoy:)

name: NEW2014! Stunning panorama bay view
description: Renovated early 2014. Stunning views over bay from viewing lounge. Two floors, well separated areas for privacy or gathering together as the mood takes you. Wheelchair access throughout the ground floor. Peak season weekly lets, Sat to Sat; minimum 4 days off season.
neighborhood_overview:
Gortduff is the most beautiful place, with lovely walks around the house or beautiful places to visit within 20 to 45 minutes - Barley Cove, Mizen Head, Crookhaven, Goleen, Schull, Ballydehob, Skibbereen, Bantry. Kenmare and the Ring of Kerry are a little further away through Bantry, or Clonakilty through Skibbereen.

During the summer there are many local markets to visit, and there are many activities locally, including horse riding, golf, sailing, or walking.
host_about:
Our home is in Hong Kong, as a family we speak English, Cantonese and Mandarin. 

We have visited the Gortduff area every year since 1987 - it has been the ideal place for a family to grow up, make friends, learn about a relaxed non-urban way of life. We have modernised Julia's so that others can share the fun and pleasures of a holiday home here. 

My interests are the Times cryptic crossword, reading pretty much anything from American crime novels through Jane Austen, walking, swimming, and chilling out.

name: Cosy Country B&B in Kinnitty near Slieve Blooms
description: Ardmore House is a large stone built house set in it's own private grounds in beautiful well maintained gardens. Enjoy beautiful views of the Slieve Blooms from the large picture windows. The house is located on the edge of the picturesque village of Kinnitty which is the trailhead for the Slieve Bloom Mountain Bike trails, the Slieve Bloom Way and many more looped walking trails .Kinnitty is less than 2 hours drive from most parts of Ireland midway between Dublin and Galway.
neighborhood_overview:
The picturesque village of Kinnitty is set at the foot of the Slieve Bloom Mountains. Ardmore Country House located in the village is a great location for walkers, mountain bikers and road bikers. Bike hire is available on site, as is bike lock up store. The Slieve Bloom Mountain Biking trailhead starts in the village.
The Slieve Bloom Mountains provide many different levels of walking, looped walks from 1 to 4 hours. You can start the long distance Slieve Bloom Way from Kinnitty or take a day trek from village to village. We provide walking maps, walking poles, packed lunches and a drying room.
if you want to gallop through the hills we can arrange horse trekking in the Slieve Bloom Mountains for you.
There are many local attractions nearby, such as Ireland's most haunted castle Leap Castle, Birr Castle Gardens with it's Giant telescope, Tullamore Dew Distillery , Lock's Distillery Kilbeggan, Lough Boora Parklands and Sculpture Park where you can cycle or walk
host_about: Outgoing, sociable, love to meet people. Have been running a bed and breakfast in my home for 25 years, and still enjoying it. I play traditional Irish music on the fiddle and often take guests with me to the local session. I am a regular walker and know the Slieve Bloom Mountain walks very well. I love to travel,  As well as knowing Ireland very well I  and have been to Cuba, South American , India and many more places.

description: Private Double or Triple room, (db & single bed)No Breakfast.Room is en-suite, has an Nespresso machine, kettle, WIFI, mini fridge, tv, hairdryer, toiletries. neighborhood_overview: We are perfectly located on Main St, For easy access to all the amazing restaurants & bars & music venues. 4 minute walk from main bus stop. Dingle is one of the main stopping off points on the 'Wild Atlantic Way' . This picturesque town, was once a small fishing village. It is now one of Irelands most popular leisure destinations. Rugged scenery, history, outdoor activities, music, amazing restaurants, fantastic pubs are some of the many reasons Dingle is top of the list on most visitors itinerary. Hill walking, music, crafts, fishing, cultural, music & food festivals also make Dingle popular with Irish visitors. We also have a resident Dolphin Fungie, daily trips available all year round. The blasket Islands are a great day trip , weather permitting. Dingle is also a Gaeltacht (Irish speaking) area, with many great historical interests, including ancient remains, Gallarus Oratory to mention one. Don't miss dining in one of the many seafood restaurants, including our own. Ashes Seafoo
host_about: I have been living in Dingle for 30 years. Originally from Midleton , Co.Cork.

name: Wild Atlantic Way . Dingle . Hot tub and Sauna .
description:
Situated in one of the most beautiful places in Ireland, just 5 miles outside the vibrant town of Dingle, our beautiful open-plan home sits at the foot of Mt Brandon, with panoramic views over the Atlantic Ocean.

Our home offers a perfect blend of comfort, luxury, and natural beauty. Whether you're looking for adventure, relaxation, or a bit of both, our home has something for everyone, including an outdoor sauna and hot tub where you can unwind and take in Dingle's breathtaking sunsets!
neighborhood_overview:
Our home is situated 5 miles outside the vibrant town of Dingle . Our local pub An Bothar Pub - is within walking distance of our holiday home . Some summer evenings there could be a music session but there is always trad. Music playing in Dingle town ... What can I say !! The Courthouse tops the bill ! Seafood in Dingle is superb with restaurants such as Out of the Blue , The Charthouse and Global Village ! Dingle just won Foodie Town of the year award in Ireland ! Ashes Pub does great pub grub and a lovely atmosphere . Can I recommend Ballydavid Harbour as a lovely safe beach for children . TPs on the waterfront is a must for local seafood and maybe a pint of Guinness !
The Wild Atlantic Way is a fantastic website to let you know what is happening in the area.
A car is an absolute necessary as the local bus only passes the house twice weekly !
(website hidden)
host_about: Love love love to travel and meet new people .!!!! Love having new people from all over the world come and stay at our home on the Dingle Peninsula and experience the sheer beauty of the place .

neighborhood_overview:
Rush was a small fishing village & is now a bustling seaside town. It has two beaches one of which the property is located on. This beach has lovely golden sand and is safe to swim in. At one end are cliffs with a Martello Tower & the other end is the harbour & local village. The village has much to offer in eating & drinking. There is also a local theatre, sailing & golf club

Dublin city centre with all its attractions is only a short train or car journey away (30 minutes)

We are also only 30 minutes to the famous Newgrange heritage site and the Hill of Tara

As we are on the east coast of Ireland the weather is mainly dry and mild.

Facilities in the local village include
Theatre
Sailing Club
Links Golf course
6 Restaurants
7 Pubs, some of which have live music and serve food
2 Supermarkets (Eurospar & Tesco) & many smaller retail business
Beauty Salons
Clothes shops
Jewellery Shop
Dry Clea
host_about: We will do everything we can to make your stay with us an enjoyable one.  We aim to be available without being intrusive.  We are a family of 5 with 3 daughters. The building dates back to 1910 & we are slowly renovating it. Every year we do a project. We opened our self catering business in 2012 and we are now working on adding a wellness retreat.  The property itself is very unique & is beachfront with direct access to a  beautiful sandy beach.

name: Gortnamacken House B&B +353877652858
description:
My home is NOT for RENT, it's a B&B.
It's a quiet spot out of town but very near the Aughty hills where you will find some lovely trails if you would like to go hill walking. We are on the route to Thoor Ballylee, Coole Park, Cliffs of Moher and the Burren. In the opposite direction is Loughrea with its famous St Brendan's Cathedral, the beautiful Grey Lake in Loughrea where you can go for a swim when the weather is in.
neighborhood_overview:
The property is situated just inside the border of the Burren Lowlands. It is set back from the road on approximately 16 acres of land. The Owenshee river runs along the end of the land which is a nice quiet place to relax and listen to the birds in the trees and the water flowing by slowly in the summer.
The house is perfectly situated for access to close by the Sliabh Aughty mountains which host amazing walk/cycle ways and paths to hike and explore . Woodville walled in garden is walking distance and is a beautiful place rich in history and a very peaceful place to visit . Thoor Ballylee in Peterswell the summer home of the famous WB Yeats is just a 15 minute drive from here and another beautiful place to see is Coole Park in Gort. From there the Cliffs of Moher, Lahinch, Kinvara and Traught Beach, Aillwee Caves, Kilmacduagh tower and Bunratty Castle. Towards Loughrea you can visit the very famous St Brendan's Cathedral with its fabulous stain glass windows and architecture . Th
host_about: I am a laid back people person. Love hosting people at the house. I like to let people feel at home when they stay with us. I love to have the chat and give a few recommendations along the way.

name: Cosy immaculate cottage, semi-rural
description:
Escape to the rolling hills of Ireland & unwind in the beautifully restored 1 bedroom cottage. The cottage features exposed beam ceilings & tasteful rustic decor that blends old-world character with modern convenience.
The open plan living space is warm & inviting, while the bedroom offers a double bed with plush linens & views of mature gardens.
Step outside to your private patio to enjoy morning coffee or a glass of wine at sunset.
This cosy cottage promises a stay full of Irish charm.
neighborhood_overview: The quiet peaceful surroundings, with sheep & cattle in nearby fields, watching the sun go down in the west, also so accessible to local shops, cafes, restaurants, cinema, bowling. A health  club, with gym, sauna & swimming pool & spa facilities is a few minutes drive away.
host_about:
Hi I'm Anna. I'd like to welcome you to this lovely part of Ireland. I love meeting guests from all over the world. You can be assured of a personal warm welcome. 
My main interests are tending to the gardens surrounding the cottage, walks along the quiet country lanes, & reading a good book whilst watching the sun go down in the west, over Crough Patrick. Idyllic!
The cottage is set in a half acre of lovely gardens. A perfect spot to relax.

name: Experience a friendly stay Galway Countryside
description:
The Lodge is an old stone stable, over 200 years part of the Dunsandle estate.
Restored and designed as a couples retreat, cosy, bright and the perfect space to relax and to slow down
Surrounded by stone walls, green fields, animals close to the woods.
About 25 minutes from Galway city with easy access to Connemara Burren Cliffs of Moher close to M6
10 minutes from Medieval Athenry & Loughrea lake
neighborhood_overview:
Day 1
Discover the enchanting Dunsandle woods and castle, on foot or bring your runner.
Visit the medieval town of Athenry, and the inspiration for one of Ireland's most famous songs 'The Fields of Athenry, in a 15-minute drive.

Day 2
Enjoy fine dining at the award-winning restaurant Lignum located 5 minutes by car from the cottage. Or taste more traditional Irish food at Maggie Mays, a pub/ restaurant renowned for its steak, located in our local, and lovely town, of Loughrea, which also hosts two excellent supermarkets; Supervalu.
Relax and enjoy Irish whiskey and great Guinness at Mary Ward's, a Traditional Irish Thatched located 2.5 miles away in the local village of Kiltullagh,

Day 3
In less than a 25-minute drive, experience the best of Irish culture, artistry, food and great nightlife, and live music in the bohemian and cosmopolitan city of Galway, Ireland's harbour city lying on the West Coast.

name: Holiday House, Ballydavid, Dingle.
description:
We loved our stay here. The house is clean and spacious in a beautiful location with stunning views. We wouldn't change a thing. -Karen July 2018
A bright, open, warm and spacious retreat in the village of Ballydavid on the Wild Atlantic Way. Within walking distance of two beaches, a restaurant and two pubs. It has four bedrooms, three bathrooms and sleeps 8 to 10 people. It has a large bright living space, a pool table, a bright airy kitchen - great for cooking and entertaining.
neighborhood_overview:
The Dingle peninsula, scenic drives, long walks both mountain and beach. The house is surrounded by spectacular scenery, situated on the Wild Atlantic Way, spectacular cliff walks and the Brandon Mountain range very close to the house. The Blasket Islands are also nearby and just a boat ride out from the Dingle Peninsula.
Their are two local pubs and a restaurant which are both very friendly. Outdoor dining is proving to be a great success in the village this year as the seating directly overlooks the beach below it. Perfect for food and drinks after a day on the beach.

name: Lovely traditional village home and organic garden
description: Six bedroom home with three full bathrooms (one ensuite), two living rooms and outdoor area right in the heart of Rathmore. The home easily sleeps ten people.  It has a fully equipped kitchen and great access to the Ring of Kerry, Paps of Anu, Killarney. Organic veggies and fresh eggs from my chickens are available and there is a great shop/bakery next door. A wonderful option for a group travelling together or a family get away.
neighborhood_overview: Killarney National Park is 20km away, Paps of Anu, Shrone, Sliabh Luachra hiking trails....
host_about:
Welcome to Rathmore, in the heartland of Sliabh Luchra, Ireland’s best known area for Irish music.

My house is in the centre of the village. I am offering a double room  en-suite, a double room  and two single rooms with a shared bathroom and shower facilities. The shared bathroom has a Jacuzzi bath. The rooms are clean, comfortable and centrally heated. A ground floor toilet and shower is also available. Guests will have access to the kitchen, gas barbeque on a covered-in veranda and an enclosed back garden. For breakfast fruit and juices are provided, cereals and freshly baked goods are available daily in the supermarket next door. I have an organic vegetable garden and I will be happy to supply a selection of seasonal vegetables for guests to cook in the kitchen.

Rathmore is very convenient to all amenities, a bus stop is 100 metres from my house and a mainline train station is one km away. Rathmore is approx 22 Km from Killarney town, the Tourism capital  of Ireland. Killarney is surrounded by an 11,000 acre National Park. The Paps mountains are 5 km from my house and are ideal for a day’s hillwalking and picnic.

Knocknagree village is 5 Km from my  house and is famous for traditional Irish music played in its pubs (bars) .

Because most of the amenities are based in rural areas guests would benefit from having their own transport. There is a cafe located in the village and Rathmore boasts  six pubs, one of which is within 500 metres  of my house. 

Free WiFi

Use ofPainting easel plus paints

Use of Fishing rods- The river Blackwater is one Km away and has excellent salmon and trout fishing.

Use of washing machine and dryer

Towels and hairdryer supplied

Tea and coffee available any time

Library/sitting room

There is no smoking in the house, smoking is permitted on the covered veranda.

I am a qualified meditation practitioner .

name: Comfortable cottage on Galway Bay
description: This  converted cottage is situated on the south side of Galway Bay (5 minutes walk to the sea), in a quiet rural setting. It is an ideal starting point for exploring Galway city, south Galway, the Burren and the Cliffs of Moher.
neighborhood_overview: You absolutely must have independent transport to stay here. Walking, the sea is 5 minutes away, and there's a great view of the Burren across the bay on a clear day. name: Patrick's self contained 1 bedroom apartment
description:
Separate , Private and Cozy, set in idyllic peaceful location.
1 bedroom self contained apartment in rural setting surrounded by panoramic views of countryside down to the Sea.
4 km from three beautiful beaches & village of Milltown Malbay ( home of the famous Willie Clancy Music Festival ) 10 km to Lahinch and Cliffs of Moher.
Nice size living room / kitchen - TV, gas top & electric oven. Double bedroom. Powerful shower.
Friendly Host.
Oil heating, parking.
neighborhood_overview: 3 miles walk to Spanish point , the Wild Atlantic Way and the beautiful village of Milltown Malbay, host of The Willie Clancy Festival.
host_about:
Hi, I'm Patrick,
I grew up in England with an Irish Mother an English Father and 5 sisters.
I moved to Cork, Ireland in 1996. I completed a sign writers course while in Cork, and moved to County Clare in 2000. I now work from home as a sign-writer. I live on my own, and take the opportunity to travel to India during the rainy Irish winters.
I love riding my motorbike, and tour Europe on the bike for a few weeks every summer .
I also enjoy the peace and quiet of where I live , the beautiful scenery and daily walks by the sea. 
I have recently started studying Art at a local college for 3 days a week.
I enjoy playing the guitar badly, riding my bicycle and swim regularly (snorkeling in the sea here is brilliant). I enjoy a good book, even though it takes me a while to get through it sometimes. Love playing my old vinyl and tape collection. Enjoy my visitors, and getting to know people from different cultures or backgrounds. Oh, and love a good game of backgammon and the odd glass of wine, or pint of Guinness. I like talking to and getting to know my guests but can be just in the background if that's what is preferred.

name: Dingle Sea View And Walk To The Beach
description:
Enjoy this STUDIO APT with lovely sea view conveniently located only 1 and a half miles from Dingle. Take a 3 minute walk to a local cove beach and come back to enjoy a cup of tea on the patio or relax by the fire. Beautiful countryside area with town only a few minutes drive away. Studio is on the backside of my cottage where I live.
One queen bed in the main area and two single beds in a small low ceiling loft with railings open to below so no children under 5. Dogs require pre approval.
neighborhood_overview: Beenbawn is a quaint hamlet of 21 farmhouses a mile from Dingle.  You can walk to town along the seaside by the lighthouse which takes about 45 minutes. The road the house is on is a  fuchsia-lined narrow road past the track of the annual Dingle Races and then the main road is narrow with fast traffic and no footpaths and I don't recommend walking it into town. Taxis are available. We are a cluster of family homes by the sea with horses, dairy cows, and sheep on the hillside.
host_about: I love to share interesting tips about Dingle and can give you lots of foodie recommendations as well as local activities. I have a dog named Teddy that I live with and he is the official greeter. I have a horse that's on the property sometimes as well. I have lived in the states and have travelled extensively. I like to explore diverse cultures and places as well as enjoy being in nature. I am a  relaxed host but I like things neat and clean.

name: Lighthouse Dwelling No. 1 - Tower House
description: Spectacular cliff edge location, wild and remote, 5km from the village of Leabgarrow.  The lighthouse, which is still operational, is at the end of the garden. The houses are two three bedroomed semi-detached houses, former Lightkeepers' dwellings.

description:

& spacious organic gardens for camping. It's 30 minutes drive from Killarney, Tralee, Dingle & Kerry airport; located on the Dingle Peninsula, facing Inch Harbour, the Magillacuddy Reeks & backed by Slieve Mish Mountains.
The boat room is a pretty ensuite double with an additional lower (Ht.120) section of the room with 3 single futon style beds, toys & books & is perfect for kids.

The walks around Dingle are extensive and they include beaches such as Binban or the Crystal beach, tidal so do watch the tides, and of course the documented Dingle Way which is all over the Dingle peninsula.
The kerry ring begins 20 minutes away in Killorglin anti clockwise you can take a drive to the exotic gardens in Kells bay shop in Cahersiveen, explore Valentia and Ballinskelligs and possibly take a boat trip to the Skelligs rock, the eight century monastic settlement . Thirty minutes away the clockwise trip of the ring of kerry is via ki

name: Unique Wooden Cabin with mountain views
description:
The cabin is perfect for anyone who wants a unique get away and to experience beautiful west cork. A 10 min drive to Glengarriff - 25 to Bantry & 20 to Kenmare . There is plenty to do and see in the area.
It is a peaceful and private place with absolutely everything you need to hand. The views and the scenery are stunning. The cabin is completely self contained set in its own garden. There are great walks and drives nearby. Or just spend time, sitting on the deck gazing at the magical view.
neighborhood_overview:
We are in the sticks, about 5 miles from the village of Glengarriff and situated in the Caha Mountains on the Cork / Kerry boarder. We are in Glengarriff nature reserve. This means our Wi-Fi is reliable but can be slow and mobile reception whilst possible is patchy.
We are within equal distance of Bantry and Kenmare close to both the Ring of Kerry and the Ring of Beara. There are plenty of mountain and forest walking trails, rivers and sea.

There are approximately 1,800 traditional thatched cottages left in Ireland.

There are many areas of natural beauty, beaches and coastal towns a short drive away: Ballymastocker beach, Downings, Dunfanaghy, Marble Hill, Rathmullen.

neighborhood_overview: Dingle is one of the main stopping off points on the 'Wild Atlantic Way' . This picturesque town, was once a small fishing village. It is now one of Irelands most popular leisure destinations. Rugged scenery, history, outdoor activities, music, amazing restaurants, fantastic pubs are some of the many reasons Dingle is top of the list on most visitors itinerary. Hill walking, music, crafts, fishing, cultural, music & food festivals also make Dingle popular with Irish visitors. We also have a resident Dolphin Fungie, daily trips available all year round. The blasket Islands are a great day trip , weather permitting. Dingle is also a Gaeltacht (Irish speaking) area, with many great historical interests, including ancient remains, Gallarus Oratory to mention one. Don't miss dining in one of the many seafood restaurants, including our own. Ashes Seafood Restaurant. Stop for a pint in one of the many quirky bars, listen to some traditional music, or attend a traditional music concert in St J
host_about: I have been living in Dingle for 30 years. Originally from Midleton , Co.Cork.

name: Arnestown Country House
description:
This beautiful, self contained semi detached house is situated in the quaint rural, seaside area of Ballymitty in South Wexford.
The house has been recently renovated and has a traditional, yet modern feel.
The house can sleep up to 6 people.
neighborhood_overview:
The area of Ballymitty is a coastal area that is steeped in natural beauty and history. It is also well known for its Irish traditional music and the nearby village of Carrig-on-Bannow plays host to an trad music festival in the last week of July each year.
There is a vast range of activities to choose from in the locality including walking, traditional music sessions, shore fishing, deep sea angling, swimming, bird watching, kayaking, surfing, horse riding, whale watching, rock climbing pony-trekking, pottery classes and much more.

The village of Wellingtonbridge is just 5 minutes by car from the house. It has a Supermarket, Post Office, Restaurants, Public House, Hairdressers, Beauticians, Car Wash Facilities, Children's Playground, Hardware/Homeware shop.

name: Cosy Converted Cowshed near Glenveagh National Pk
description:
The Cow Shed at Neadú is a cosy, rustic converted byre situated on our property in a very tranquil scenic area.
The view from the cottage looks towards the beautiful Glendowan mountains and Glenveagh National Park.
Ideal for a peaceful retreat or a great base from which to explore Donegal.
neighborhood_overview:
We are centrally located in a beautiful part of Donegal, close to most of its attractions.
The cottage is nestled in a valley 3km from the scenic village of Fintown.
The river Finn is known widely for its salmon and trout fishing and permits are available locally for fly-fishing.
In Fintown village, you will find the only operational narrow gauge railway in Donegal. It runs for
5 km beside Lough Finn, which is overlooked by Aghla and Scraig mountains.
The local village has pubs, a church, school, health centre and library.
Please note that we are not within easy walking distance of pubs.

The towns of Glenties, Dungloe, Ballybofey and Letterkenny are 15 minutes, 15 minutes, 25 minutes and 30 minutes drives respectively. There you will find restaurants, pubs and supermarkets.

There are many stunning beaches within a 30 minute drive, offering beautiful walks and a choice of sports such as kayaking, surfing, golf and horse-riding, all
host_about:
We moved to Donegal eighteen years ago and converted our traditional byre and stone cottage where we now happily live with our two children.

In 2016 Pete completed our second little rental, The Hide, followed a few years later by The Birdbox. 
We call our little collection of spaces Neadú which is the Irish word for nestle and love the fact that we can be more self sufficient, working from home while meeting all the lovely people who visit us.

We look forward to welcoming you to one of the most beautiful, unspoilt parts of Ireland!

name: Carr's Cottage - Country Retreat
description: A beautiful location for a socially distanced Irish holiday within a few minutes drive of wonderful beaches. Carr's Cottage nestles among the rolling hills of Fanad, County Donegal, just 4 miles from Carrigart. Located on a private laneway on our family farm, with stunning views of Mulroy Bay and the imposing Muckish Mountain. Carr's Cottage is only minutes drive from cafes, golf courses, fishing and breathtaking walks. A great location for exploring the wonderful Fanad and Rosguill Peninsulas.
neighborhood_overview:
Fanad is one of the most beautiful places in Ireland with rugged coastlines, sheltered bays with idyllic secluded beaches framed by majestic heather covered hills. It is a Gealtacht (Irish language speaking area), located in North Donegal around 40 minutes north of Letterkenny, the principle town in the county. Although secluded, amenities are plentiful in the peninsula – from surfing to kayaking, beachcombing to pitch'n'put, from beautiful Atlantic drives to breath-taking hillwalking, the Fanad and Rosguill peninsulas have something for everyone. Some of the best golfing in the world is a few minutes' drive away at Portsalon or Rosapenna Golf Links. The peninsula is dotted with coves and small harbours and fishing is not only an attractive offer for the interested tourist but a way of life for some of the peninsula inhabitants.

Be sure to check out the world famous imposing Fanad Lighthouse, not far from the property, or take a trip to the picturesque seaside villages of

name: Could not be more central
description:
Located right in the centre of Dublin's gorgeous shopping district this is a perfect location for a visit to Dublin.

Our cosy and comfortable guest room and a scrumptious breakfast each morning await you.

We really want you to have a fabulous stay so we would like to make sure you know that:-
1. Being so central, it can get noisy at night. If you are a light sleeper you may like to bring earplugs.
2. The apartment is up 3 flights of stairs with NO LIFT - a built-in workout each day ;)
neighborhood_overview:
Being right in the centre of Dublin the apartment is surrounded by some of the best restaurants, pubs and bars in Dublin. Dublin caters for every taste in terms of style and cuisine and everything is within minutes of the apartment. Advice is at hand to make sure you make the best possible choice for a night out on the town, a cosy romantic dinner for two or something quick but delicious.

Shopping is a breeze with lovely boutiques and all of the Grafton Street shopping just steps away. It is a pleasant walk over the river to access the shopping available on the North Side of Dublin on O'Connell Street and Parnell Street where the larger department stores are located.

The apartment is located in the same street as a supermarket and also the best delicatessen in Dublin. Shopping for food and other basic necessities could not be easier.
host_about: Victoria has been living in Dublin for a number of years.  She finds Dublin a fabulously social place with truly friendly people and a real village feel.  Victoria loves to travel, cook and read.  She is also a keen kitesurfer and climber. She loves meeting people from different parts of the world and to share, in a small way, their travel adventure.

There is also a large supermarket with an ATM and off-license and the award-winning restaurant- The Courthouse. There are also many eateries from Indian, Chinese to English. There is a hairdresser, beauty salon and Taxi service also available.
If you want to enjoy a day out shopping in a bustling town then the large urban centres of Sligo, Donegal Town and Enniskillen are only a short 30 or 50 minutes drive respectively from the property.

name: Cahirciveen Marina, Ring Of Kerry
description: 2 bedroom 2 bathroom property, FREE WiFi, recently renovated terraced house with private back patio.
neighborhood_overview:
This home from home can be used as a base to explore all the ring of Kerry region has to offer. Located a stones throw from Cahirciveen Marina and a 5 min walk from the main town.

Beautiful white sandy blue flag beaches nearby as well as historical sites such as the Skelligs Rock. The skelligs rock is a UNESCO World heritage site, boat trips can be arranged from Portmagee a picturesque fishing village just 10 minutes away.

The Cahirciveen area has just recently been awarded “gold tier” status in the International Dark Sky Reserve, the first time it has been awarded in the northern hemisphere. It is designated only for particularly clear and bright night skies, with easily visible phenomena such as the aurora, the Milky Way and meteors.


Valentia Island with spectacular views from Geokaun Cliffs, Skelligs Chocolate factory at St Finians Bay all nearby.

name: Idyllic views in Connemara, Galway.
description: With stunning, unspoiled views as far as the eye can see of lakes, mountains and wild bogs, this lakeside property will give you the complete Connemara experience while also being in close proximity the village of Oughterard, Galway City and the Wild Atlantic Way.
neighborhood_overview:
Oughterard is a traditional village in the West of Ireland nestled beside Lough Corrib (the largest lake in the Republic), at the start of the Connemara Mountain Range and only 17km from Galway City- The City of the Tribes.

Oughterard is an ideal base to tour Connemara, Galway County and Galway City, Mayo and the Burren in County Clare. Lough Corrib is famous for its brown trout and salmon fishing and Oughterard is the main angling centre on the lake. The angling season open on Lough Corrib in mid-February and finishes in late-September and is at its busiest in May during the Mayfly season. Boats and boatmen can be hired locally. Golf and horse riding are also available locally. Other points of interest locally are the nearby 14th centuary Aughnanure Castle and 19th centuary Glangola Lead and Silver Mines, which are both open to the public. There are many traditional pubs in the village with great places to dine nearby.

name: Heatherhill Farm Cottages in Letterfrack village
description:
Heatherhill Farm Cottage is a large house on a wonderful equestrian farm.
It has 6 bedrooms, two bathrooms and large kitchen, dining and sitting room.
It is located in Letterfrack beside Connemara National Park and Diamond Mountain and close to Kylemore Abbey and lots of white sandy beaches,
The village of Letterfrack has three pubs, three restaurants, a supermarket, church, post office , Connemara National Park centre, hairdressers, beautician and library.
There is a good bus service.
neighborhood_overview: It is a beautiful, friendly , safe place with all amenities - shop, restaurants, pubs, out door walks and runs and direct access to the Atlantic Ocean. neighborhood_overview:
Rush was a small fishing village & is now a bustling seaside town but still maintains the small town feel with friendly locals & everything you need on your doorstep. There are lovely restaurants & bars. 2 good supermarkets and plenty of smaller excellent local traders.

At one end are cliffs with a Martello Tower & the other end is the harbour & local village. The village has much to offer in eating & drinking. There is also a local theatre, sailing & golf club

Dublin city centre with all its attractions is only a short train or car journey away.

We are also only 30 minutes to the famous Newgrange heritage site and the Hill of Tara

As we are on the east coast of Ireland the weather is mainly dry and mild.

Facilities in the local village include
Theatre
Sailing Club
Links Golf course
6 Restaurants

neighborhood_overview:
Galway European City of Culture for 2020!!!!!

Where I live is in the Claddagh! Ever heard of the Claddagh ring? Well welcome to its home! Not only that we are next to the best nightlife Galway has to offer but also the tastiest award winning restaurants! Just pop over the bridge and find yourself in the newly named Latin Quarter...otherwise known to us as Quay street. The best place to watch the world go by or see the local personalities...and we have quite a few!!!! Or sit in the sun on the Spanish Arch where you will meet everyone and anyone! We have an escape room just around the corner for a rainy day and for sunny days there are several options for beautiful walks.. whether you want a walk along the canal to the university or to see the boats at the harbour or walk along Nimmo's pier and along the salthill promenade. See our local marine life at the Galway Aquarium which is just 10-15 minutes from our apartment. Have a night of traditional music and singing at the near
host_about:

name: Lakeside Haven quiet relaxing countryside retreat
description: Quiet peaceful space in a rural countryside setting, surrounded by nature on scenic Lough Cutra Drive just 9 km off the M18 Motorway Gort junction.  This self contained guest suite is an extension of our home. neighborhood_overview:
'Lough Cutra Drive', a scenic route that connects the Gort - Portumna road to the Gort - Scarriff road, route signposted at both ends. Relax and enjoy the beautiful sunsets over the lake.
The surrounding countryside is peaceful with amazing views, plenty of wildlife, popular with walkers and cyclists (Cyclists do the circuit of the lake and surrounding area - 20 km approx).
A pleasant 5 minute stroll away, there is a small lakeside beach; which makes a very good large paddling pool for small children. This is a popular spot with local people during the warmer months.
There is a children's playground in Gort Town and for those who enjoy walking - Gort River Walk is accessed at the rear of Aldi; Coole Park Nature reserve of woodland and wetland, has marked trails, a visitor centre and tearooms, and a picnic area in the Walled Garden. Walks and family activities during Summer.

neighborhood_overview: The village of Waterville is famous throughout the world for its championship links golf course & superb sea trout and salmon angling. The area is blessed with some of the most spectacular scenery in Ireland & offers walkers and cyclists endless possibilities for sightseeing & touring. The area boasts an abundance of ancient historical sites, among these are the 6th century Skelligs UNESCO World Heritage Site, the Stone Fort at Loher and 6th century ruins on Church Island. The area is particularly popular with artists & nature lovers. There are endless possibilities to experience the indigenous flora & fauna first hand. The village has attracted numerous celebrities over the years, from Charlie Chaplin to world famous golfers, such as Tiger Woods and Mark O'Meara.

Our local surf school, Beach Bar Surf School, is a 2 min walk from the house. Lessons and equipment rental are available

The Beach Bar is a 3 min walk from the house and you will find food, traditional music and a great atmosphere. There is also a tiny campsite beside the house that caters mostly to small groups and families. Very nearby are some great surfing spots, Easkey and Stranhill being the most famous. We are also close to the Ox Mountains, a stunning location for cycling and walking.

Sligo town is about a 25 min drive from the house and guests will find a wide variety of activities and places to eat there.

neighborhood_overview: Dingle is one of the main stopping off points on the 'Wild Atlantic Way' . This picturesque town, was once a small fishing village. It is now one of Irelands most popular leisure destinations. Rugged scenery, history, outdoor activities, music, amazing restaurants, fantastic pubs are some of the many reasons Dingle is top of the list on most visitors itinerary. Hill walking, music, crafts, fishing, cultural, music & food festivals also make Dingle popular with Irish visitors. We also have a resident Dolphin Fungie, daily trips available all year round. The blasket Islands are a great day trip , weather permitting. Dingle is also a Gaeltacht (Irish speaking) area, with many great historical interests, including ancient remains, Gallarus Oratory to mention one. Don't miss dining in one of the many seafood restaurants, including our own. Ashes Seafood Restaurant. Stop for a pint in one of the many quirky bars, listen to some traditional music, or attend a traditional music concert in St J
host_about: I have been living in Dingle for 30 years. Originally from Midleton , Co.Cork.

name: Gannet Cottage Skellig Ring Portmagee
description: Gannet Cottage is one of six self-catering cottages standing on the shore of the beautiful Portmagee Channel with spectacular views across to Valentia Island. Located on the Skellig Ring and Wild Atlantic Way.
neighborhood_overview:
Our cottages and farmhouses are located on the world famous Wild Atlantic Way! We are only 4 kilometers from Bray Head which is 1 of 15 signature discovery points on the entire 2,500 kilometer route which goes from Donegal to Cork. There are also numerous discovery points in the locality; we recommend that people download the Wild Atlantic Way app for further information.
Our properties are located just 3 kilometers from the charming fishing village of Portmagee. Portmagee is located in the South West of Ireland in the beautiful county of Kerry. The cottages sit on the coastline and look across the water to Valentia Island. They are on the waterfront with large open lawns, natural hedging and direct access to the seashore. We have two moorings in case you wish to bring your boat!
host_about: Portmagee Seaside Cottages is a family run business. The family is made up of Elizabeth and James and our children Paul (living and working in London and New York), Aisling (living and working in Australia) and Roisin (living and working in Cork). We also have a farm with pedigree Charolais cows and ducks. The Camden Street/Portobello area is one of the very best in Dublin – lively, cultural, full of pubs, coffee shops, restaurants, music venues and night clubs. Whelans, Dublin's most important music venue is around the corner on Wexford Street. Pub-of-the-year winners Devitt's is even closer and also has live music every night.

Other places of interest in the immediate vicinity include: St Patrick's Cathedral, Marsh's Library, the National Concert Hall, the Museum of Literature (MoLI), the Grand Canal, the Iveagh Gardens, St Stephen's Green … and many more.

Grafton Street, Trinity College, the Parliamentary buildings, the National History Museum and the National Gallery are within a radius of 10-15 mins walk. So too are Dublin Castle and the wonderful Chester Beattie Library.

The thriving nightlife of George's Street, South William Street and Dame Lane – and the more tourist-focused Temple Bar are within 15mins walk.

name: Private Large Group Accommodation
description:
A hostel built for grown ups with hotel quality at affordable prices

Specialising in groups and located in the picturesque mountain village of Kilfinane, Co. Limerick, offering the ultimate in comfort, cleanliness, space and hospitality.
neighborhood_overview:
Shops, pubs, restaurant and take-aways are just a stroll up the street.
40 minutes from Limerick city and 50 minutes from Cork city.

Activities locally

-Mountain biking
-Clay pigeon shooting
-Horse trekking
-Hill walking
-Road biking.
-Yoga walks
-J J’s Brewery tours

A little further afield

-Aqua park offering kayaking, axe throwing, jacobs ladder, abseiling and many more
-Go Karting
-Adventure park offering exciting outdoor activities including bushcraft, paintballing, survival courses, 3D archery, splatball.
host_about:
Being a self-employed Builder/Carpenter based in and around Dublin for over 25 years, I, Séamus, had no choice but to come up with something different or emigrate after the downturn in 2008. While planning to travel abroad for work, I bought my old family home in Kilfinane, Co. Limerick which my parents had built in the early 60’s and reared their 7 children there .

While planning what to do I was returning home a lot more as our junior hurling team, Blackrock, won the All Ireland gold in 2009 and I found myself falling in love with the old village, it’s mountain and it’s people again. I decided to invest my future back in my home town and came up with the idea of a luxury hostel.

Then I went about designing it and finally securing planning in May 2012. I then secured funding and started building in August 2013. Thankfully with a lot of luck and help from good friends, family, neighbours and especially some very understanding contractors and workers, we opened our doors in June 2014. 

Even more thankfully, in July 2015 my wifeTeresa, a farmer’s daughter from Sligo, working as a National School Teacher in Ballyfermot, moved down and now it’s just the two of us who run, work and live in Ballyhoura Luxury Hostel.

description: Executive apartment, bedroom with SUPER KING  size bed ( 6 ft. Wide) and kitchen with all new appliances, bathroom equipped with Roca sink unit, wc and bidet, Power shower and chaise lounge. Sitting room  to relax with Samsung smart 55" TV  DVD player & tranquil  location. CHARGE YOUR EV overnight.
neighborhood_overview: We have lived and worked  in the South East of Ireland  all our lives ( except when in Middle East) and have comprehensive knowledge of the area, am now retired and  willing to share same which would include places like for example Mount Juliet Golf Course and hotel which is adjoining the apartment, the entrance is 200 meters away and the house is a scenic 20 minutes walk away or one mile. (Please note that the Thomastown Gate for entrance to Moun t Juliet is currently closed due to Covid 19 restrictions, Mount Juliet is open and it entails of round trip of 5 Kms, to get in) Enniscorthy and Vinegar  Hill, Wexford town, Kennedy Park, Dunbrody Famine ship experience, Waterford Crystal, Dunmore East fishing village, Passage East, Kilkenny City , Castle, Cathedral's.  If you are into mountain trekking, Mount Leinster is 25 miles away and summit is 2610 feet high gives panoramic views of Wexford coastline round to Tramore in Co. Waterford. North you will see Carlow, Bagnalstown and west tow
host_about:
Sheila here, I am retired from the nursing profession after 40 years service in the local hospital. I have lived, worked and reared my family in Thomastown since getting married to Michael. My hobbies included reading, listening to radio and podcasts when walking, keeping up to date with current affairs and visits to the theatre. My real passion is cooking which I can indulge in since retiring. I also travel extensively to far "flung places"  with Michael who doesn't allow the grass to grow under my feet!!!

Michael:-
Retired Irish Police Officer who then followed a hobby as a photographer into the professional realms and had my own studio in Thomastown. Had a wonderful time as a professional photographer, met Clint Eastwood and many other famous people along the way. I photographed over 500 weddings and have many happy memories tucked away in negative form in a filing cabinet. This is now converted in the attached listing.  I have lived in Jerusalem with my family during the 1970's and worked with UN.  As a result love to travel back there  and keep a keen interest in developments in that part of the world. In the past year (2013). Love cycling and have toured Ireland on an electric bicycle, lazy maybe but lovely when going uphill. Enjoy plays, classical music but also oldies from 50's and 60's. Reading with Kobo ereader  and using the ipad and other gadgets floats my boat also! Love nothing better than getting up early in the morning, going for a 5 mile walk,and listening to some podcasts, news or music on earphones. neighborhood_overview:
Description
This detached property is located in the charming village of Ballylongford, Co. Kerry, in an area of historic and natural beauty, beside the estuary of the river Shannon. On your doorstep you can enjoy the iconic pubs, and shops that this tranquil village has to offer, and visit the remains of a medieval castle and monastery.
The beautiful seaside town of Ballybunion with golden beaches, and world renowned golf course, is only 9 miles away.
Fishing (river and sea) and boating facilities including dolphin watching are a short drive away.
Also within a ten minute drive is the historic town of Listowel, where you can enjoy the Arts and Culture of north Kerry, with festivals such as Writers Week, the beautiful St Johns Theatre, and Listowel Horse Racing Festival. name: Amazing Sea Views Apartment on Wild Atlantic Way
description:
The converted Georgian house, built in 1839, is located on the Dingle Peninsula along the Wild Atlantic Way, a short walk from Ballyferriter Village. Full of character and style, the property has "The best views from the windows in the area" according to the National Geographic Traveller. The nearest beaches are within 1 mile. For Star Wars lovers, the setting of The Last Jedi can be seen from the apartment.
This apartment is one of four in the property. Breege, your host, lives on the grounds.
neighborhood_overview:
Watching the sun go down from my house or driving 3mls to the viewing spot is a (website hidden) is the furthest out piece of land you will rest on before you reach America from Europe.Its also home to the second highest mountain peak in Ireland.The Dingle Penninsula much loved by everyone is a calming,relatively unspoilt land where you can still feel and experience living in another millenium.
You are 50 mtrs from village,some nights you can hear the best trad.music and singing and also sample great fish and the local brew.The cliffs that you view from my home are now the location for the new Star Wars movie The Last Jedi,Ryan’s Daughter and Far and Away.
host_about:
Love traveling,cycling and reading.I have 3 adult children,all living away from home.We have lived in this house for 45 years and it’s been in the Granville family for 100 years.
I love sharing with you my guests and giving you every helping hand to make your stay on the Penninsula the most enjoyable.

neighborhood_overview:
The small seaside village of Waterville has often been referred to as the ’Jewel’ on the famous Ring of Kerry.Nestled on the edge of the Atlantic Ocean, hugging the shores of Lough Currane (famous worldwide for salmon & specimen sea trout) and enjoying a magnificent backdrop of lush, rugged mountains, it is little wonder that Charlie Chaplin fell in love with this idyllic, picturesque (email hidden)aplin returned to Waterville for many years with his wife Oona and their children, as, according to members of the Chaplin family, Waterville afforded him a tranquil haven where he could enjoy spending time with his family in relative anonymity. Many locals remember him strolling along the seafront promenade which runs along the centre of the village, his privacy always respected.

One of Chaplin’s favourite pursuits while in Waterville was fishing on Lough Currane.

His grandson Julien (a regular visitor to Waterville today) recounts a story of his grandfather having had
host_about: Enjoy my work - welcoming and taking good care of our Guests,  a great pride of place - something very special about living in a place where people come from all over the World to see and visit Skellig Michael our 6th Century Monastic Settlement , to enjoy our Dark Skies and ever changing land and seascapes, walk along the Seafront promenade - enjoy an ice cream cone and do nothing but to breathe in the space and beauty , we are lucky enough to live here and to ensure all our guests enjoy their experience of all South Kerry has to offer. I enjoy well cooked good food especially our local Seafood - Kerry Lamb and small local produce, Veg and Breads,  also Foreign Cinema , Jazz Music , Radio and Internet, Irish Social History and of course family.

name: Beach Cottage, Carnivan, Fethard on Sea, Wexford
description: A stones throw to two beautiful white sandy beaches, Carnivan and Baginbun. Our self catering 3brm cottage (sleeps 6) is on the Coast Road, Fethard on Sea.  Two miles from the Fethard village.  Cottage has a timber deck with picnic bench and great countryside views.  Suitable for families with young children as once the gate is closed the garden is fully enclosed. The cottage is well insulated with woodburning stove and bright with dual aspect windows. Hi speed fibre broadband.

The cottage is approx. 2 miles from the lovely seaside village of Fethard on Sea where you will find 2 pubs, one of does food - Georgios Greek Restaurant), a fully stocked Londis convenience store, open 7 days, café, fish & chip takeaway, Chinese restaurant and takeaway, chemist, gift/souvenir shop and during Summer a Tourist Office.
host_about: Originally from New Zealand now married to Mike who farms in Fethard on Sea.  Love living by the water, fishing in our timber boat and tending our veggie patch. I love to entertain, cooking adventurous foods along with plenty of BBQ's, and love to meet new people.

name: Double Room with en-suite
description: With en-suite
host_about:
Welcome to Rathmore, in the heartland of Sliabh Luchra, Ireland’s best known area for Irish music.

My house is in the centre of the village. I am offering a double room  en-suite, a double room  and two single rooms with a shared bathroom and shower facilities. The shared bathroom has a Jacuzzi bath. The rooms are clean, comfortable and centrally heated. A ground floor toilet and shower is also available. Guests will have access to the kitchen, gas barbeque on a covered-in veranda and an enclosed back garden. For breakfast fruit and juices are provided, cereals and freshly baked goods are available daily in the supermarket next door. I have an organic vegetable garden and I will be happy to supply a selection of seasonal vegetables for guests to cook in the kitchen.

Rathmore is very convenient to all amenities, a bus stop is 100 metres from my house and a mainline train station is one km away. Rathmore is approx 22 Km from Killarney town, the Tourism capital  of Ireland. Killarney is surrounded by an 11,000 acre National Park. The Paps mountains are 5 km from my house and are ideal for a day’s hillwalking and picnic.

Knocknagree village is 5 Km from my  house and is famous for traditional Irish music played in its pubs (bars) .

Because most of the amenities are based in rural areas guests would benefit from having their own transport. There is a cafe located in the village and Rathmore boasts  six pubs, one of which is within 500 metres  of my house. 

Free WiFi

Use ofPainting easel plus paints

Use of Fishing rods- The river Blackwater is one Km away and has excellent salmon and trout fishing.

Use of washing machine and dryer

Towels and hairdryer supplied

Tea and coffee available any time

Library/sitting room

There is no smoking in the house, smoking is permitted on the covered veranda.

I am a qualified meditation practitioner .

name: The Glens-Great base for ecotourists
description:
This self-catering apartment has 2 rooms (1 double bed and 3 single beds), located in the heart of the vibrant town of Manorhamilton - with arts centres, pubs, castles and lots of character. It's ideal for anglers, cyclists, and hillwalkers.
WiFi 16mbs. Please note that the apartment is not wheelchair accessible as there are steps up to the apartment.
neighborhood_overview: Great place to stay as it is very close to areas such as Sligo, Bundoran, Enniskillen to name a few. Plenty of little local areas to drive to and see. The beaches in Bundoran are close for summertime activities as is the Organic Centre for those who want to see organic gardens and maybe pick up some great seeds for their own homes. Plenty of lakes, rivers, forests and mountains to visit, along with many historical sights along the way. They don't call it lovely Leitrim for nothing! You won't be let down as there is plenty to do for everyone.
host_about:
The Glens Centre is a small intimate music and theatre venue in an old methodist church in the heart of Ireland's beautiful, unspoilt north west. We are a favourite with performers and audiences alike - specialising in theatre, trad, folk & americana music, recordings, and literature.

We are fortunate to have the apartment  with the centre, which has just been renovated, to a high standard, where individuals or groups can come - not just to be near the cultural activities in the centre, but as a perfect base for fishing, hillwalking, cycling and the many other activities you can enjoy in the north west.

name: The White House Ballydehob Ireland
description: The White House is set on an acre at the head of a secluded valley, and sleeps 8 people. It's located in the hills above the towns of Bantry, Skibbereen and Ballydehob and is ideally situated for exploring the spectacular coastline of Cork & Kerry
neighborhood_overview:
The White House is set at the head of a valley underneath Mount Kid. The surrounding countryside consists of wild bogland and lush farmland. Lovely local walks provide panoramic views over beautiful West Cork and from the top of Mount Kid you can see all the islands of Roaringwater Bay
The House is set off a small country road with quiet and secluded gardens.
host_about:
We live in West London with our 3 children, but spend our holidays in Cork and Mayo near our parents, uncles, aunts, cousins.... We are both self-employed - working in the music and internet industries.

We brought The White House in 2007 having outgrown our 1 bedroom cottage in Mayo. We were looking for a larger house, with an exciting garden for the children. Pat's mothers family come from Skibbereen and we have always loved the atmosphere of west Cork.
West Cork has the most stunning coastline and gorgeous villages, but has not been ravaged by tourists. The music festivals, and pub sessions are exceptional; the scenery breathtaking; the island hopping great fun; and the local people so welcoming.

description:
Enjoy staying in a large house in the center of Ballsbridge. Adjacent to Grafton st, RDS, Aviva Stadium, 3Arena, UCD, Bord Gais Energy Theatre and The Convention Centre Original home of famous dress designer Sybil Connolly!!!
Built 1850, original features intact!
Amazing and Unique - luxury 4 double bed period style Victorian House, will give you and your guests a unique insight into Dublin culture with restaurants/bars on your doorstep
Views of River overlooking Ballsbridge
Has WiiU
neighborhood_overview:
Our neighbourhood is in one of the best locations in Dublin. Site seeing tour bus stop located adjacent to house.
It takes 15 minutes to walk to Grafton Street and Trinity College or along the canal and visit the pubs favoured by many of our Irish poets and writers. Theatres, the Aviva Stadium and the docklands are just a stroll away.
Dublin bikes are available to hire at budget rates and well worth it. There are excellent pubs and restaurants to suit all tastes. Parks, museums and galleries all within a short stroll.
Herbert Park -
Next door Herbert Park is a green oasis spread over 32 acres of prime Ballsbridge land. It is named after Sidney Herbert, the father of the Earl of Pembroke who owned the land that Ballsbridge was built on. Some features of the park date back to the Dublin International Trades Exhibition, a kind of mini World Fair held in Dublin in 1907. name: Private double room in cottage home
description:
Own car ESSENTIAL. (Not suitable for cyclists) Minimum 2 nights. Child-free zone.
One of 3 rented rooms, our beautifully restored Irish cottage offers all the home comforts in a tranquil rural setting, close to the Wild Atlantic Way, Doolin, Lahinch, the Cliffs of Moher, the Burren and the Aran Islands.
Optional Continental breakfast provided at €5 per person
neighborhood_overview:
Discover the ‘real’ Ireland. Our renovated stone cottage sits towards the top of the mountain above Doolin with views of Liscannor Bay and Lahinch beach. Lahinch and Doolin are 12 minutes drive down the hill.
We are surrounded by farmland...our road, often referred to by our guests as a lane, is single track with grass growing in the middle. It is perfectly negotiable by tractors and trash carts, so it’s no problem for cars.
We have no light pollution so the night skies are amazing
You are more than welcome to sit in the gardens and read or absorb the silence before going down to the village for food every evening.

.

name: Ash House Irish Country House B&B
description: At our traditional Irish country Bed and Breakfast you will experience a warm and friendly atmosphere in our relaxing family country home set on its own grounds in the scenic south Kildare countryside.
neighborhood_overview:
We are one hour’s drive from Dublin city centre, and from Dublin Airport. 
Situated just 10 minutes off the M9 (Wexford, Waterford, Kilkenny) and 15 minutes off the M7 (Kerry, Cork, Clare, Limerick).

We are also just a short drive (15 minutes) to some of Kildare’s most visited and exciting attractions such as the well known shopping location of The Kildare Village, as well as The Curragh Racecourse and Punchestown racecourse.

Visit the beautiful stud farm and its idyllic grounds at The National Stud and Japanese Gardens or have a game at one of Kildare’s many fine Golf courses.

We are also ideally situated for those attending functions at Rathsallagh House Hotel and Golf Club (10 minutes drive).

name: Cosy Cottage  Midway between East & West Coast
description:
Cosy comfortable self-catering traditional Irish cottage in Kinnitty village at the foot of the Slieve Bloom Mountains midway between Dublin and Galway. Tastefully decorated, the cottage is set in it's own private grounds on a quiet country road. 3 bedrooms free WIFI, & a large garden.
For the outdoor enthusiasts the cottage is beside a variety of Slieve Bloom Mountains looped walking trails, and the Slieve Bloom Mountain Biking trails which start in the village, Lough Boora Parklands.
neighborhood_overview:
In the village of Kinnitty at the foot of the Slieve Bloom mountains just 2
minutes walk to centre of the village. The Kinnitty trailhead for the Slieve Bloom Mountain Biking trails starts in the village. Kinnity also has it's own artisan beer, brewed at by Slieve Bloom Brewing Company and Kinnitty Castle has it's own Whiskey.

Near Ireland's most haunted castle Leap Castle, Birr Castle Gardens with it's Giant Telescope, Tullamore Dew Distillery , Kilbeggan Distilleryfor Lough Boora Parklands and Sculpture Park. Nearby heritage sites include Clonmacnoise, the Georgian town of Birr, Emo Court House and Gardens.

For the outdoor enthusiasts the cottage is beside a wide variety of looped walking trails which can be accessed at Kinnitty, Cadamstown, Clonaslee, Glenbarrow and the long distance Slieve Bloom Way and the Slieve Bloom Mountain Bike trails which start in the village.

Mountain Bikes and Ebikes are available for just across the road from
host_about: Outgoing, sociable, love to meet people. Have been running a bed and breakfast in my home for 25 years, and still enjoying it. I play traditional Irish music on the fiddle and often take guests with me to the local session. I am a regular walker and know the Slieve Bloom Mountain walks very well. I love to travel,  As well as knowing Ireland very well I  and have been to Cuba, South American , India and many more places.

name: Stunning thatched property: Nanny Murphy's Cottage
description: Featured in the Irish Times, Independent & sustainable building websites; this unique property is all about traditional Irish culture, heritage & passionate craftsmanship. Quiet, cosy and romantic, it boasts many authentic features (cob walls, open fireplace, exposed beams) that transport you back to old Ireland! Includes modern conveniences for comfort. Great central location in beautiful countryside - ideal for exploring Ireland's gems. This isn't just a place to stay - its an experience...
neighborhood_overview:
The cottage is located in a small, tight-knit community who will welcome you with open arms. Local shop (4 min walk), Arvagh town (5 min drive - pharmacy, pubs, banks, post office, petrol station), larger towns of Longford or Cavan (30 min drive). Nearest pub (5 min drive). Arvagh is famous for being the only place in Ireland where you can stand where three provinces meet (Ulster, Leinster and Connacht).

For walkers: there's Bruse Mountain, many lakes (e.g. Lough Gowna), beautiful Irish countryside with trails. Fishermen: you'll be spolit for choice. Interested in history, there's: heritage sites including Aughnacliffe’s 5,000-year-old portal dolmen, abbey ruins, Corlea Trackway Visitor Centre (Iron-Age bog road) and more. Explorers and Sports: kyaking, boating, water sports, equestrian, golf, hiking & cycling. Fun lovers: sample Ireland's finest, rural pubs and local hospitality. Don't mention the Guinness?!

host_about: Self employed and self taught protector of vernacular buildings..I have a passion for the stories surrounding the people who built and lived in them.    And then to make these stories and buildings come to life and bring them to a new audience....

name: City 2 bed Cosy Cottage
description:
Completely renovated Artisan Cottage - In Dublin 8.
Purpose built in 1900 for the Guinness factory workers (the factory is close by).
Old style on the outside, chic, modern & cosy on the inside (small)
2 double bedrooms - sleeps 4
(5 at a push)
neighborhood_overview:
I love that it's so close to town.
The Supermarket is on the corner.
host_about:
I love living in this city and I love living so close to the action.
It really is a 15 minute walk to the centre - I consider George's St the start of the action. (If your Guide book is saying the centre is O'Connell St, then maybe officially yeah, but you wouldn't want to hang out there. Trust me, it's George's Street) Food, music, shopping, coffee, people watching - all taken care of in that area
St. Patrick's Cathedral is nearby with the park adjoining it. And up the hill from that is Christchurch. 
I love food - eating it, cooking, buying it, having people over, so I adore that right by the house is a Lidl supermarket with great fresh produce - the fruit and veg are great and they usually have a selection of fresh fish too. 
Not to mention the bakery which bakes all day!
It's so easy to fall out of bed, round the corner and get whatever I need. Even after a big night out.
They have a good selection of beer and wine too.


This is a small city so I bike everywhere, the Dublin City bikes are great if you're a visitor. There are stations everywhere. But I think what visitors mostly say about this city is how accessible it is, you really can walk everywhere (well, to most of the worth seeing places)



Before considering booking please note:
I do actually live in this little house, most of the time so it's only available when I'm on holidays or at weekends (I'll go stay with friends or my parents)
I will try to consider any requests that I get. I know how tough it is to get a nice place in a capital city.
Please let me know when you'll be arriving so that I can do my best to be available or get a keyholder to be there. This isn't always possible as I work 9 to 5 Monday to Friday. 

I'm mentioning this because it's a question I got asked, but yes bed linen and towels are provided!
Please let me know how many are staying and I'll leave out plenty.

I provide shampoo, conditioner, showergel, toothpaste and face wipes also.

There are notes in the house for the heating, hot water and wifi password.

There's usually tea, coffee, condiments, oils, dressings, spices, herbs and basic food stuffs in the house (rice, pasta, noodles, cous cous, beans) - please feel free to use any of it .... if it's there!
And if there's anything in the fridge at all, and you like the look of it, help yourself.

name: Bunkroom for 2 close to Cliffs of Moher (3)
description:
Own car ESSENTIAL (not suitable for cyclists/pedestrians as no public transport nearby. It takes nearly 2 hrs to walk from Doolin or Lahinch)

Minimum 2 nights stay.

Apologies, no children or dogs.

One of 3 rented rooms in our home. Single bunk beds in private room.
Shared kitchen, Sitting room and bathroom.

10 minutes drive to Doolin, Lahinch, the Burren National Park and the Cliffs of Moher.

Continental breakfast included.
neighborhood_overview:
Peace and quiet. Surrounded by farmland with grazing cattle
Lovely gardens with great views over Liscannor Bay
Very little light pollution so the stars are amazing.
From the top of the hill overlooking Doolin and the Aran Islands you can see fantastic sunsets.
The pubs in Doolin serve really good meals.
The beautiful, safe beach at Lahinch for swimming and surfing, only 12 minutes by car.
World class golf course in Lahinch.
A ferry can be caught from Doolin to visit the Aran Islands or take a cruise alongside the Cliffs of Moher, which are about 10 minutes away by car.
We are on the edge of the Burren National Park and very close to many of the locations used to film the Father Ted TV series.
host_about:
Christy and I are  English but live in Ireland. Christy is a musician/ singer/songwriter and I used to teach English.  Now I build mosaic sculptures
.
We love travelling and have visited most parts of the world. We lived in New Zealand for 6 years and welcome fellow travellers to share our home, and amazing locality. 
We are non smokers, have 3 cats and are eco friendly. Our garden is organic and what we don't grow, we source locally.

name: John Joe's Farmhouse Skellig Ring Portmagee
description: John Joe's Farmhouse is a traditional Irish farmhouse with fantastic views of the mountains and countryside in Portmagee. Located on the Skellig Ring and Wild Atlantic Way.
neighborhood_overview:
Our cottages and farmhouses are located on the world famous Wild Atlantic Way! We are only 4 kilometers from Bray Head which is 1 of 15 signature discovery points on the entire 2,500 kilometer route which goes from Donegal to Cork. There are also numerous discovery points in the locality; we recommend that people download the Wild Atlantic Way app for further information.
Our properties are located just 3 kilometres from the charming fishing village of Portmagee. Portmagee is located in the South West of Ireland in the beautiful county of Kerry. John Joe’s farmhouse is located at the foot of a small mountain less than 1 kilometer from the sea. We have two moorings below our seaside cottages in case you wish to bring your boat!
host_about: Portmagee Seaside Cottages is a family run business. The family is made up of Elizabeth and James and our children Paul (living and working in London and New York), Aisling (living and working in Australia) and Roisin (living and working in Cork). We also have a farm with pedigree Charolais cows and ducks. We have very good local knowledge of all that is going on, we can recommend nice places to visit and know all the local boat and activity operators. In our spare time (which can be limited!) we are avid walkers. We would be happy to advise our guests on walking routes in the locality and time permitting might also be available to lead our guests on a walk.

name: Dublin-Killiney-Period Villa-Room 2of2 + Breakfast
description: Beautiful private bedroom(+shared Guest bathroom),in restored Georgian Villa in historic picturesque Killiney, South Dublin- with continental style breakfast. Located in a quiet neighbourhood at foot of Killiney Hill,near Killiney Bay/ beach. Easy access to  Dublin City, Dalkey and Dublin/Wicklow Mountains. Walking distance to DART (train-35/37mins to City Centre)+ bus services to Dun Laoghaire/Dublin City etc  and near to  LUAS(tram-Green Line) and  a Dublin Airport Aircoach  702 at Dalkey
neighborhood_overview:
Our period home is located in a quiet neighbourhood at the base of Killiney Hill. This is in the historic area of Killiney with it's many period houses. It is near to the splendid Killiney Bay with its European Blue Flag accredited beach that will suit hardy swimmers- there are bookable saunas on the beach that are ideal for pre or post swim use. For the less intrepid it is still a wonderful place to go for a stroll.
The historic Heritage Town of Dalkey is nearby. With it's numerous restaurants and bars and added to it's literary past it is a place well worth a visit-from our home it is just a short one stop hop away on the DART. For the more strenuous guests a lengthy walk to Dalkey could take in Killiney Hill and it's obelisk together with the spectacular 360deg panoramic views-these include views of: Killiney Bay from Dalkey to Bray Head( that has been rightly likened to Sorrento Bay in Italy), to the Sugarloaf Mountains in County Wicklow and to Dublin Bay and Dublin City.
host_about:
From Dublin, Ireland. Retired Civil Engineer, living with my wife Cathy.
Our primary interests are; cycling, hiking, skiing, travel, cooking and gardening 
We often host dinner parties for family and friends.
We frequently travel abroad and  have been to many countries including those in Europe, North America, Australia and Asia.
Our life mottos are; to live and enjoy life to the full and age is just a number

name: Michaeleen's Manor - The Quiet Man B&B
description: A B&B themed on The Quiet Man film, with character named bedrooms and memorabilia. Ensuite rooms, cooked breakfast, free parking and free wifi. 24 miles from Westport and Galway, surrounded by Connemara scenery, 1 mile from Cong - Ireland's most beautiful village  and the only village featured on TripAdvisor's 2018 top ten Irish destinations. Only 5 minutes walk from The Lodge at Ashford Castle and Lough Corrib. Tours of The Quiet Man film locations & Museum available
neighborhood_overview: The closest village, Cong, is an inland island surrounded by water, with nature and history conspiring to make Cong fascinating. Cong is considered the oldest settlement in Ireland outside of the Boyne Valley, with stone circles, cairns and monuments. 2000 acres of woodlands and forest surround the village for beautiful lakeside and riverside walks. Cong is home to the world famous Ashford Castle and 10 caves. It is also the location of the filming of the John Wayne classic The Quiet Man. Guided walking tours and chauffeur tours of The Quiet Man film locations depart from The Quiet Man Museum daily.
host_about: We have hosted guests in Cong, Ireland's most beautiful village, since 1985. Prior to that, Margaret was a chef at Ashford Castle Hotel during President Ronald Regan's stay at Ashford Castle in 1984. Gerry is the Quiet Man tour guide and regularly entertains guests with Quiet Man stories.

neighborhood_overview:
Peaceful haven 3km from cashel.
4 min drive but not suitable for public transport. In the heart of The Golden Vale yet close to major transport routes. Tipperary is a county of immense natural beauty, with a unique and ancient heritage. Shaped by the rugged Galtee Mountains and the River Suir, Tipperary has some of Irelands most breathtaking scenery and dotted with towns and villages. Cashel is home to the iconic Rock of Cashel. One of the most spectacular tourist attractions in Ireland and one of the most visited. Cashel’s rich history is reflected in its built heritage, from prehistoric earth mounds to mediaeval monasteries and fortified town houses, a Georgian Cathedral and a 21st century Library (which holds regular exhibitions, workshops and concerts).
With 3 mountain ranges nearby its a mecca for the outdoors. Cycling routes are endless! Sadly most visitors just overnight in Tipperary and miss out on so much. Instead of rushing from Dublin to Kerry like the masses, wh

I am happy to help you in planning your trip with my top secret "Helens Top Tips".
