name: Mongolian Yurt @ Inch Hideaway EcoSustainable Camp
description: Inch Hideaway is situated walking distance (15min) from Inch Beach. This yurt has beautifully hand painted woodwork and sleeps up to 6 people. Sitting on a raised platform the yurt is insulated and has an electric heater and is furnished with beds and all the extra comforts. You'll have access to the comunal kitchen with your own cooking station, dining area in the Barn, BBQs, Pizza Oven, electric shower and its own toilet nearby.
neighborhood_overview:
East Cork is an undiscovered jem! In the range of 5 to 10 min drive there are a lot of beautiful beaches and woods, eco/outdoors activities, amazing restaurants and pubs in a neighbourhood that is very welcoming!
Inch Beach (15 min walk) has a surf school renting all the gear you'd need for surfing or coastering.
Poc Ar Buile is an outstanding pub only 20 min walk from the campsite,
a jem of rural pub!
host_about:
Hi, I'm a Cranio Sacral therapist with a big passion for good food, music and Natural/Sustainable Building.
My amazing partner is Colleen. She runs the Inch Hideaway campsite and she's a Horticulture therapist and we share the love for natural building, travelling and meeting new people from all different walks of life.
Together we've build most of  what you'll find at our place (the rest was build by our amazingly skilled friends&family)!
It's an eco sustainable camping/glamping, therefore we invite our guests to be aware and respectfull of the the environment, people and animals that are on the grounds.

name: TRAM 50M | WALK TO CENTRE 20MINS | WIFI
description: Enjoy a peaceful and clean single room for one with WIFI and shared bathroom in a cosy 100 year old townhouse, with free on-street parking. The city centre (O'Connell Street) is just a 25/30min walk or 15 minutes on the tram, which is less than 50 metres from the house (Cabra stop). Dublin Zoo, Phoenix Park, Botanic Gardens are close by. Two very friendly dogs live in the house.
neighborhood_overview:
The neighborhood of Cabra/Phibsborough is relatively quiet and residential, with a real community feel. It's fantastic to be within walking or tram distance of Dublin city centre but without the madness of staying right in the heart of it! The Phoenix Park, the Zoo, the National Botanic Gardens, historic Glasnevin Cemetry, the Mater Hospital and O'Connell Street are all close by, plus pubs, cafes and local shops. If you enjoy rooting through charity/second hand shops, Phibsborough village is a mecca for this!

For fitness fans, there are so many options right on the doorstep, with lots of parks and the beautiful Royal Canal.

name: Tig Admaid: secluded seaside cabin with hot-tub
description: Here at Killaha Holidays we would love to welcome you to our beautifully located large 3 bedroom cabin right on the shore of Kenmare Bay just 2 miles from Kenmare town. Watch the otters, sea birds and wild deer from your deck overlooking the beach. Relax in the outdoor Jacuzzi or inside beside our wood burning stove. A spacious house, secluded and private, it was originally built by my grandparents as a holiday home in the 1950s, now successfully renovated for the 21st century!
neighborhood_overview:
Quiet and private cabin right by the sea, with otters and deer (and even the occasional sea eagle!) for company!
We also host guests in our off grid glamping sites, Oak Tree and Hazelnut Yurts, situated in our woodland area nearby. The yurts can also be booked through Airbnb.
Kenmare town is 2 miles away but unfortunately the road is not suitable for walking.
host_about: An artist based on the Beara Penninsula, I have hosted on Airbnb for many years - providing my family with an income from our cosy yurts or spacious 3 bedroom cabin. Our acres of woodland disguise pre-famine potato ridges, terraced fields and even an old famine road, built in the 1800s to access food from the shore and the beach where we now have our own oyster farm. We have plenty of shellfish growing here in the wild at KillahaHolidays too!

name: Bundoran. Sea View.
description: Breathtaking views over Donegal Bay, & on the Wild Atlantic Way.   This is the view from the back garden, Beautiful  equipped holiday home. Great surfing area, 1 mile from Bundoran with  many bars, & restaurants. Beside the Drowes river which is famous for  fishing. Ideal location for birdwatching ( Birding ) Good touring base for Sligo, Leitrim, Fermanagh. Please note the house is only available from Saturday to Saturday during July & August. No pets
neighborhood_overview: Great views over Donegal Bay. The Drowes River which flows into the sea at the back of the house is one of Ireland's best salmon fishing river & has produced the first salmon of the season for a number of years.  Directly across from the house is a very nice restaurant called the Silkie which is open 5/6 days per week. Unfortunately the view from the front is not as nice as the back as the mountain view is blocked by a two story building. The neighbourhood is very safe & also very quiet. There is a small public outdoor library in the village of Tullaghan which is 5 minutes walk away  also an outdoor gym. Most important of all is a defibrillator also in the village.
host_about: I live in Dublin. The house listed here is our holiday home which we have for 20 years. As it is our holiday home there is everything there that you could possibly want & is a real home from home. I am married with 4 grown up children & 5 grandchildren.  As we  live in Dublin we  will not be around to meet & greet our visitors, so hope this will not take from your welcome & enjoyment of your stay. We are both retired & on hand  by  phone to deal with any of your requests.

name: Artist's Pad near Guinness Factory
description: Our beautifully renovated home is a 20 minute walk from Trinity College and is seconds from the Guinness Storehouse in the heart of old Dublin. We have one double bedroom, two singles and a great garden with a hammock.
neighborhood_overview:
The Liberties is one of the oldest parts of Dublin. It's a working class inner city neighborhood full of charm and local colour.

We have lived here for ten years and love it. the area. Our house lies almost in the shadow of the vast Guinness Factory complex and every few days the air is infused with the sweet scent of roasted hops.

The Guinness Storehouse is Ireland's busiest visitor attraction and boasts 360 degree views over the city from the Gravity Bar on the roof.

The Irish Museum of Modern Art (IMMA) is a few minutes walk away and Newmarket Square plays host to brilliant food markets and vintage clothing & furniture fairs every weekend.

Fallons (on the Coombe) is one of the best pubs in Dublin, small and local with a great pint of Guinness and the nearby Fumbully Cafe (on Patrick St) has amazing food and is jammed with Dublin creatives gazing into their laptops.

Meath St is straight out of a Roddy Doyle novel and Francis St
host_about: I am an artist and I make films, paintings and large scale public art pieces. I live in Dublin with my Australian wife who is an arts publicist and our 5 year old son. We try to get to Australia once a year if possible and spend most weekends traveling around Ireland visiting friends and exploring the countryside. I love water, I swim as often as I can and I'm saving up for a wood fired hot-tub.

name: Central Dublin Comfy Victorian Charm
description: Big bright room with private bathroom. Our home is a very comfortable charming Victorian terraced redbrick cottage near the centre of Dublin. It has lots of character and period features and is on a pretty, quiet street in  Broadstone less than fifteen minutes from the hustle bustle of the city centre. This shouldn't need to be said, but just to be clear, people of all colours, all faiths and none, and every sexual orientation and gender identity are welcome. We just want you to be nice!
neighborhood_overview: The Neighbourhood, Broadstone is a collection of streets of Victorian redbrick cottages surrounding a gorgeous little Park. It's a perfect example of an oasis - calm and quiet but just minutes from the City centre and all of its amenities. James Joyce lived two doors away where he wrote those nasty letters which were discovered under the floorboards!
host_about:
Hi I'm Aoife and that's my daughter, Clara. After years of great travels around the world meeting great people and seeing amazing things, it's time for new adventures for me: namely, being a Mum to Clara and being a host to travellers to my beautiful hometown of Dublin. Look forward to meeting you and spilling a few secrets of Dublin's hidden gems! 

Clara and I love being Airbnb hosts and are honoured to be Airbnb Superhosts. We love meeting new people and like our guests to have a home from home experience. Some of our guests have said it felt like they were staying with friends, which is exactly what I was hoping for!

name: Giltraps Townhouse Group Room
description: Giltraps Guesthouse is located in the charming village of Kinnitty in Offaly, at the foothills of the Slieve Bloom Mountains. This purpose-built accommodation provides all modern practical amenities that any guest requires for a comfortable stay.
host_about:
Giltraps Townhouse & Glamping is located in the charming village of Kinnitty in County Offaly, Ireland and at the foothills of the Slieve Bloom Mountains. This purpose-built guest accommodation provides all of the modern practical amenities that any guest would require for an independent and comfortable stay. 

Kinnitty Village is a ninety minute drive from Dublin, Galway, Shannon and Rosslare. It is the ideal location to use as a base to explore the Irish countryside, hike, walk and / or cycle in the Slieve Bloom Mountains, or attend a wedding at Kinnitty Castle Hotel. 

Giltraps is located in the centre of the village, a fifteen second walk from all local amenities and both churches.

OUR ROOMS
All of the en-suite rooms are bright and airy with central heating throughout. There are five en-suite guest rooms in Giltraps Guesthouse. The rooms cater for every type of guest request from single occupancy to family rooms catering for up to four persons, including child cots. The entire accommodation is a smoke-free area.

The beds, as comfortable as you will find, comprise of orthopaedic mattresses and cotton sheets. All of the bathrooms feature power showers with luxury bathroom amenities. Some of the additional amenities available upon request include iron & ironing boards, hair dryers & straighteners and shoe polish. 

Giltraps Yurt
For a luxury glamping yurt experience we can provide a very comfortable interior accommodation up to four guests.

OUR BREAKFAST
At Giltraps Townhouse & Glamping, our breakfast offering is quite unique. A Breakfast hamper consisting of floury bap with bacon, sausage and egg, freshly baked croissants and selection of tea and coffee. Please note that breakfast is not included in listed rates.

name: Room & Private Bathroom, Female only
description: Enjoy a pleasant and safe stay in a quiet cul-de-sac in the lively village of Ranelagh. Our house is beside a bus stop and a short walk from the Luas tram. The Miltown Institute is a 5 minutes walk away. The room comes with its own private bathroom. Short stays on request.
neighborhood_overview:
Ranelagh still retains its character as a village even though it is only minutes away from the centre of Dublin. It has a long history including being the location of ancient battles and of the first hot air balloon flight in Ireland. In 1785, only two years after the first manned flight, Richard Crosbie was the first Irishman to make a manned flight when he successfully flew in a hot air balloon from Ranelagh Gardens to Clontarf. Padraig Pearse, one of the leaders of the Easter Rising in 1916, established St . Enda's school on September 8, 1908, in Cullenswood House, Ranelagh. All the major Easter Rising locations in the city centre can easily be reached.
There are over 30 restaurants, coffee shops and pubs in Ranelagh should you not want to go as far as the city.

name: White Strand Beach House - Wild Atlantic Wanderer
description:
!!!LOCATION, LOCATION, LOCATION!!!
This fabulous 3 bed detached holiday home on private site is located just a stones throw from the White Strand Beach, Buncrana Municipal Golf Course, The Inishowen Gateway Hotel, The Drift Inn Bar & Restaurant and local convenience store....yet...it is also just 1km from Buncrana Main St.
neighborhood_overview:
Buncrana Town and nearby surrounding areas have so much to offer for travellers.

The local scenic beauty is most definitely a huge attraction. Sandy beaches, numerous viewpoints from rolling hills, cliffs and mountains.

An ideal way to enjoy the scenic beauty of this area is by taking the "Inishowen 100" route plan by the local tourist industry which shows off Inishowens best features throughout a 100km journey. The Wild Atlantic way follows much of the Inishowen 100 and is well signposted.

The nature of the local people is welcoming and warming. People here have a genuine and caring interest in other people and this is a most unique and pleasant experience for travellers from largely populated areas to sample.

A relaxing holiday in the countryside is what you will get yet there are cities with large populations as nearby as 20 minutes drive.

Buncrana town itself offers numerous attractions for a visitor:-

Sandy beaches
host_about:
I'm a busy working mother of 3 boys living in beautiful Buncrana, Co. Donegal, Ireland with its sandy beaches, rolling hills and fresh air! 
As proprietor of the Wild Atlantic Wanderer Donegal self catering homes brand, I love sharing my properties with others and meeting people from all over the world.

host_about:
I enjoy hosting and have met lots of very interesting people. I am in and out of the house  a lot but am always available to meet guests and am available by phone/e-mail if you require my help if I'm not home.  
My home is off the beaten track so if you are looking for the bright lights of the city then this is not the spot for you.  
IMPORTANT INFORMATION
The Eircode for Google Maps to bring you to my house is R95 D96V.  If you do not have access to Google Maps, please follow the instructions below:- 
From Kilkenny - Take the N77 (Castlecomer Road) out of Kilkenny and follow tthe road until you come to a junction about 6km outside Kilkenny which will be signposted Durrow/Ballyragget to the left (N77).  Keep on this road and drive through Ballyragget towards Durrow.  DO NOT TAKE THE FIRST ROAD WHICH IS SIGNPOSTED LISDOWNEY.  Instead, continue on the N77 for about 2km until you pass Glanbia Factory on the left.  The next road on the left immediately after Glanbia is signposted for Lisdowney (Road Number L5833)4km.  Take this left and drive for 2.7km.  My home is on the right hand side.  No gate.  Gravel driveway.  With a bit of luck, you have arrived!
From Durrow - Follow signs for Ballyragget.  Just before Glanbia Factory, turn right on road signposted Lisdowney (Road Number L5833) 4km.  Follow road as detailed above.

name: Arts Studio - creative space - for 1, 2 or more
description: Quirky, cosy little arts studio, with traditional Irish character. Hidden in the heart of town, in this 'Middle Kingdom'. Kitchenette, shower-bathroom & treehouse balcony. Ideal for attending special occasions/arts festivals/work-stays.  It is a favourite of visitors from home & abroad. Step & duck through a small door in the big gates, into an unexpected, tranquil haven - a 'magical' courtyard garden. Sleeps 2 on comfy divans, as double/singles. Breakfast provided. See details!
neighborhood_overview:
The arts studio is close to the two hotels, shops and cafés, and short walks or drives to assorted venues and attractions. Birr is a renowned Georgian Heritage town, with the impressive main attraction of Birr Castle Gardens and Historic Science Centre.

With its fascinating histories from monastic times onwards, it is a town strong in the arts and there are excellent community resources, including a fine theatre, town parks, an excellent leisure centre. There are great small shops, lovely cafés, a few of which serve locally grown and organic foods. They all have fine coffees and some bake their own breads and cakes and daily specials. Nearby, a few good restaurants for dinner - particularly the 'posh' gourmet Sanjay's Kitchen Indian restaurant. Also The Thatch Pub & restaurant (walk or drive 1km); Kelly's Pub on The Green; Hackett's at The County Arms Hotel - both close by.

Pubs? Of course! A small list of recommended imbibing places is available in the rooms -
host_about:
An 'occasional' writer, artist/designer. Family background was in historic property restoration - homes open to the public. Later lived & worked in London & New York for architects as a colour & materials specialist.
Very happily settled back in Ireland in this busy, arty heritage town, running Tin Jug Studio (first art gallery in the county) - now occasionally open for seasonal children's art classes, events, screenings, exhibitions, etc.

name: Clonbur House -  Studio village apartment
description:
This practical studio apartment is located in Clonbur. The apartment boasts the perfect location in the heart of a beautiful and welcoming village. Tastefully furnished throughout . This is the perfect touring base for the West of Ireland and Connemara regions, ideally located between Lough Corrib and Lough Mask for fishing. Bakery, supermarket, bars and restaurants within walking distance.
Forest walking,cycling trails and mountain walks available right from the doorstep.
neighborhood_overview:
This is the ideal touring base for the west of Ireland. Clonbur is centrally located between the beautiful lakes of Lough Corrib and Lough Mask surrounded by mountains and woodland. The locals are friendly and welcoming. You can treat yourself to the award winning bakery in the village and enjoy a picnic in the woods. There is traditional music in the highly rated local bars and restaurants. Mount Gable is situated to the west of the village, the walk is generally easy with panoramic views over the lakes, forest and countryside. You can walk/cycle the 7km to the famous village of Cong and Ashford castle through beautiful woodland trails. Clonbur has a fantastic playground.

All attractions of the West are easily visited from this location. Coastal drives and numerous beaches are within a 40 minute drive. We are within a hours drive from Galway city ,Westport , Clifden.

Ireland West Airport - 1hr
Shannon Airport - 2hrs
Dublin Airport - 3hrs

name: Room 3 Good Value, Central & Secure letting.
description:
An en-suite bedroom with a shared kitchen
Located in village center.
Close to all amenities.
Free secure parking, with private entrance.
Full kitchen to cook your own meals.
A perfect base for touring Connemara and landmarks such as Kylemore Abbey, Connemara National Park, Clifden's Sky Road and The Wild Atlantic Way, all 1 hour drive from apartment.
neighborhood_overview:
A friendly Connemara village with plenty of pubs, restaurants & culture.
The beautiful Owen Riff is just 250 yards walk away, while lough Corrib lake is 1 km walk from apartment. You can rent boats locally, go on a Corrib cruise to visit the historic Inchagoill island or go further on to the world famous Ashford Castle.
Fishermen love the lake as it's the largest wild brown trout fishing in Europe. In my cafe downstairs I have the largest wild brown trout ever caught on the lake, a 23lb 12oz beauty caught by Ceri Jones.
Steeped in history, Oughterard boasts numerous attractions including Glengowla mines, Aughnanure Castle, Brigit's Garden and Corrib cruises.
In the cafe I have a visitors attraction wall that informs tourists of places to visit, local walks and interesting local stuff like famous Harry Clarke stained glass window, literary works by James Joyce and his local connections and writings by Walter Macken.
A perfect base for touring Connemara Kylemore
host_about:
I like Irish traditional music especially the fiddle which I am learning to play.
Friendly, outgoing and enjoy meeting new people.
life motto; pretend you’re doing it for yourself

description:
LOCATION, LOCATION , LOCATION.
PARK THE CAR AND EXPLORE.
TOWN CENTRE APARTMENT.

TWO BEDROOM SLEEPS 6.
GORGEOUS HIGH CEILINGS,COMPLETELY OVERHAULED AND RECENTLY RENOVATED .

neighborhood_overview:
Westport..is many things...a great place to live, a great place to visit and a fabulous place to go out in...Winner of Ireland tidiest town on a number of occassions, the best place to live in Ireland as voted by the readers of the Irish Times, has the best 99 in Ireland...westport has it all....the odd, the lovely , the practical and the occasionally ridiculous.
It hosts varied festivals throughout the year..Arts, Blues, Music, walking and running...all the human conditions are catered for....from the mind to the body... A planned town surrounded by and close to gorgeous mountains and beaches.Connemara is within a half hour drive...Achill Island is 22 miles the other direction...a great town to use as a base while you explore the wilds of Mayo... For families and Cyclists we have The Greenway, One of Ireland first designated cycle ways is very popular,bikes can be hired locally , bikes can be locked on the outdoor balcony, the balcony is very safe and secure..Westport House is we
host_about: walk out the  door and let the memories in, I am from westport and know the area very well. I am the father of three girls so I know first hand it is possible to have every sort of a day in westport, the surrounding country side is packed with the potential to have an action packed holiday.The greenway  cycleway is only minutes away from the apartment..Mountains, ocean, beaches, lakes, fishing, walks...all surrounding westport..and the town  has cafes, restaurants, quirky shops, interesting nooks and crannies...for families, couples ,lovers of life........westport has it all...open the front door and let the memories in..

description: Our house is 170 years old and has been lovingly restored by ourselves. We have three spare bedrooms, each  with a double bed, so we can accommodate 6 adults easily.  Located in a quiet area, 5 minutes drive to Letterkenny town. Please note that if you need more than one bedroom to please check availability with us before you book.  Letterkenny is the ideal place to be based for touring Donegal, the Wild Atlantic Way, and the numerous attractions that are nearby.

name: ROCK COTTAGE, Wild Atlantic Way, Schull,West Cork
description: Exceptional traditional Irish cottage set in the grounds of one of Lord Bandon's Hunting Lodges. Surrounded by beautiful gardens, walks and trails including stunning sea views overlooking Dunmanus Bay & the Atlantic. Ideally situated to explore the Wild Atlantic Way. Close to Schull, Durrus & Goleen. Nearby beautiful beaches. Dog friendly. Schull has boutique shops, restaurants, pubs, sailing and a Sunday market.

There are music, literary, film festivals in the summer close by.

Da wir die meiste Zeit hier in Deutschland in unseren Unternehmen tätig sind, möchten wir unser Ferienhaus auch anderen Nutzern überlassen.

name: Wild Atlantic Way, Drumcliffe Sligo
description: 2 bedroom apartment with all amenities as the base for a great holiday, in the heart of Yeats Country, on the Wild Atlantic Way route and overlooked by Benbulben mountain. 1km from Yeats' Grave, 5km from Lissadell House and Lissadell beach, 8km from Sligo town, Rosses Point, Glencar Lake & Waterfall and Streedagh beach.  Lough Gill and Mullaghmore are around 15 km away.
neighborhood_overview:
The apartment is 8km north of Sligo town and 5km away from the beautiful Lissadell beach. Several other beaches, including Rosses Point and Streedagh, are only minutes away by car. Yeats's grave is located 1 km away and this apartment is located right in the centre of the Yeats country. There are golf courses, excellent fishing rivers, quiet country roads for cycling and peaceful walking tracks in this area. Benbulben, Truskmore and Knocknarea offer challenging mountain climbs. Horse riding can be enjoyed nearby. Glencar Waterfall is just across the border in County Leitrim (7 km away).

Given our proximity to the coast, this is an excellent base for water-based activities and boat trips can be arranged locally, to include trips to the deserted monastic settlement on the island of Innismurray.

The beaches at Strandhill (17km away), Rosses Point (8km away) Mullaghmore (16 km away) and Streedagh (10 km away) are famous for surfing and are lovely to stroll on. Lis

I love entertaining and making people feel welcome, which is why I enjoy the airbnb experience so much.

name: Self Catering Studio-Perfect for Couples
description:
Our cool and comfortable flat is a perfect oasis in the gateway to Connemara. It comfortably fits two an extra bed can be provided, and is centrally located on a quiet street just off the town centre.
Secure bicycle lock up can be provided.
Close to all amenities and loads of secure parking. Enjoy our village in style.
neighborhood_overview:
A friendly Connemara village with plenty of pubs, restaurants & culture.
The beautiful Owen Riff is just 250 yards walk away, while lough Corrib lake is 1 km walk from apartment. You can rent boats locally, go on a Corrib cruise to visit the historic Inchagoill island or go further on to the world famous Ashford Castle.
Fishermen love the lake as it's the largest wild brown trout fishing in Europe. In my cafe downstairs I have the largest wild brown trout ever caught on the lake, a 23lb 12oz beauty caught by Ceri Jones.
Steeped in history, Oughterard boasts numerous attractions including Glengowla mines, Aughnanure Castle, Brigit's Garden and Corrib cruises.
In the cafe I have a visitors attraction wall that informs tourists of places to visit, local walks and interesting local stuff like famous Harry Clarke stained glass window, literary works by James Joyce and his local connections and writings by Walter Macken.
A perfect base for touring Connemara Kylemore
host_about:
I like Irish traditional music especially the fiddle which I am learning to play.
Friendly, outgoing and enjoy meeting new people.
life motto; pretend you’re doing it for yourself

name: Cosy 3 BR House 15m From Centre
description:
Welcome to my peaceful house only a short walk from the hustle and bustle of the city centre. The 3 bedroom mews house is nestled on a quiet lane in Phibsborough, just around the corner from the beautiful Victorian Blessington Basin.

It's my home, and I'm delighted to offer it to visitors to Dublin. It's perfectly located for exploring at only 10 minutes walk from O'Connell St, 20 minutes walk from the Liberties, and 20 minutes from Grafton Street. Also well connected to buses and the Luas.
neighborhood_overview: Phibsboro is one of Dublin's coolest neighbourhoods and offers plenty to eat and drink through cafés like Two Boys Brew, restaurants like Loretta's and pubs like The Hut and McGeogh's. Further afield at just 10 minutes walk away you'll find Parnell Street with lots of delicious Asian restaurants and hip cocktail bars like The Big Romance. 15 minutes away is the gorgeous and newly pedestrianised Capel Street with buzzy restaurants and iconic LGBTQ+ venues like Panti Bar.

description: Delightful SNUG one bedroom apartment conveniently located in Wicklow on the boarders of Dublin and Kildare.  Approximately a half hour drive from Dublin Airport. The capital city Dublin is within an easy bus ride.  Locally, a drive or walk at Blessington lakes is a must or a visit to Rusborough House.

The famous Japanese Gardens is also within easy reach.  There are several golf courses nearby.

name: Bright en-suite bedroom + shared kitchen/dining
description:
Bright and spacious en-suite bedroom in a tranquil semi-detached house in quiet cul-de sac residential area in Terenure.
City centre is 4.7 km distance away, 9 min walk to the bus stop, bus every 15 mins and a 19 minute bus journey - total journey time 28 mins on buses 9 and 54a.
16 Bus to/from the airport, at the Airport go to Zone 15 for the 16 bus. Takes between 1hr and 1hr 15 mins and then a 10 min walk to the house.
neighborhood_overview: The neighbourhood is a quiet and very safe residential area of Dublin. Very restful and quiet street as there is minimal traffic here and cars do not pass by this house as it is a cul-de-sac. Area is a nice contrast to the hustle and bustle of the city, yet conveniently located for easy access into the city centre via public transport. Good choice of local shops nearby to buy food in and nice restaurants close by, if you want to eat out and get a feel for the local area. City Airport local bus 16 goes from the Airport to the end of the Road leading up to the estate (Mount Tallant stop) and can take about an hour to an hour and 20 mins depending on the traffic. The dearer option would be a cab and the advantage of this is that, you would reach the house in about a half an hour. The buses 9 and 54a go direct into the city centre and the Next Bus Dublin Free app will tell you when the next bus will arrive at the stop on Kimmage Road
host_about: I am interested in and organise local arts events in a community context. Also interested in Education and tutor young people in Maths and Science. I enjoy hosting and meeting new people and I  continuously improve the service provided, based on guest feedback and observation

name: STREEDAGH BEACH, WILD ATLANTIC WAY
neighborhood_overview:
Nature is all around within easy reach, except for the sound of the sea. Via a meadow in front of the house, you can reach cliffs where you can discover any kind of sediments or just marvel at the surf. To the rear, the view goes straight out onto the Streedagh sea bay with extensive sandy beach and a small view to the right leads to the Benbulben. You should definitely not miss a climb there!
By the way: The term "nature" is not to be the same here with complete wilderness. A gardener maintains the garden so that you can use and enjoy the lawn in good weather (the view photo into the garden is from winter, therefore the unfinished lawn).
host_about: Als Irlandfan habe ich ein eigenes und ein Cottage meiner Familie liebevoll restauriert und nutze es mit meiner eigenen Familie mehrmals im Jahr als Oase der Urlaubsruhe. Dort möchte und brauche ich nicht auf Komfort verzichten und kann gleichzeitig das Urige der irischen Gaeltacht erleben. Gerne gebe ich Euch Tips für Anreise, billigen Mietwagen oder Unternehmungen, egal ob Ihr das Haus bucht oder woanders hinfahrt.

name: Large country home (12 mins Athlone) off N61
description: Relax in style! This 190 sqm rural retreat, just 12 minutes from Athlone, stands on 1.25 acres. Whether you’re travelling for business or pleasure, it has everything you need: award-winning mattresses; high-speed WiFi; ample on-site parking; flexible check-in/check-out; dedicated work space; high-quality appliances (inc washer/dryer). No bedrooms share a wall; two are en-suite. Private, comfortable.  Stargazers will love the rare *dark sky*!  Sleeps 1-7.  Ask about early check-in/late check-out.
neighborhood_overview:
Hazel Hollows is the perfect base from which to explore Ireland in every direction (or as a stop-over en route to somewhere else). Turn left out of the gate from the house and before long you’ll find a stone marking the geographical centre of Ireland. As you walk along the lane, you’ll encounter Lough Ree. Our ‘hood is an interesting mix of ancient and modern. Further down the lane you’ll find a sign pointing to the ruins of the medieval town of Rindoon (‘Rin Duin’). Not far from Rindoon lies St John’s Wood—one of the oldest surviving natural woodlands in Ireland. This little corner of the world attracts a wide variety of birds. There are many trails to explore, with different views around every corner.

LECARROW HARBOUR
Here you can picnic, relax or take a walk along the canal. Padraig Corcoran offers guided boat tours on Lough Ree plus fishing boats and gear for rent. If you prefer terra firma, he has bicycles for hire too. Please see our guide book for his co
host_about: I'm a Celtic mutt and world traveller who detests hotels, no matter how luxurious.  I love the whole airbnb concept and it's my pleasure to share the family home my parents built three decades ago with those looking for much, much more than a tired or sterile vacation rental.  I work hard to make sure your stay is stress-free. I make it a point to be easy to reach before, during and after your stay.

name: Traditional Stone Cottage.
description:
Come relax and unwind in our beautiful two bedroom traditional stone cottage completely refurbished and extended in 2006.
The cottage is situated on a large private garden in peaceful private scenic countryside.
The cottage can sleep 5 adults and an infant.
Excellent location for exploring the North and West of the country as well as fishing, boating, walking or just relaxing.
Free 500gb WI-Fi
neighborhood_overview:
The Cottage is in an excellent fishing/walking area with lots of lakes and the Shannon Erne Waterway close by.
Si More hill is a 10 mindrive-moderate walk with great views and Neolithic tombs. Castlefore lake is a 20 min walk and Lough Scur is a 5 minute drive. The fishing lake, Lough Roan is a 10 minutes drive away and the Iron Mountains - a very scenic area for hiking is 20 minute by car.
Keshcarrigan is a 5 min drive and has two pubs, Gerties Bar has food and music at weekends, Taylors Mc Keowns Pub has excellent food seven days a week.
The nearest large town is Carrick on Shannon (approx 20 minutes by car) which has Tesco and Aldi, river cruises, cinemas, bowling, banking, shopping and lots of bars.
Ballinamore has large supermarkets, petrol station, take aways and of Bars.
Sligo is one hour drive, surfing and sea fishing in Salthill, Yates grave and Lisadell are worth visiting.

description:

We've recreated it, with a twist - Cape Killala style!

neighborhood_overview:
Why Killala?
Genuine, authentic Irish seaside village - an abundance of pubs, a cute restaurant, shops, garage and supermarket. But, best of all, a beautiful bay on the Atlantic, overlooking stunning Batra Island, surrounded by beautiful, unspoilt beaches.
Why Killala?
Why not!

name: Lofty Eyrie at Temple Bar
description:
I was asked by Airbnb to say what makes my place special-It's the top floor of a five storey 18th Century Dublin Townhouse, with no lift!
I lived here for 15 years and miss it still.
Dublin Castle at one end of the Street, River Liffey at the other.
High living room - roof terrace for the sunny days - the quiet of a Sunday Mornings
The apartment is suited for 4-6 guests. It's cheaper for 2, the price increases with extra guests. If 1-3 "book instantly" long term, I may cancel within 24hr
neighborhood_overview:
The whole of Dublin is currently a very popular tourist destination. Dublin is now very cosmopolitan, its rapidly expanding technological sector has drawn in a huge number of people of different nationalities to live and work.
It's also a very popular tourist destination at the moment, with the busiest area only a block away. Dubliners are almost always happy to give directions (and opinions) to visitors, so ask them!

The city benefits from a number of green spaces, the nearest is at Dublin Castle, at the top of the street, the biggest is the huge Phoenix Park, 25 minutes walk away. In between, Trinity College park is 5 minutes away, St. Steven's Green and Merrion Square, are within 15 minutes, near the main southside shopping district of Grafton Street, and the National Museum, Gallery and Parliament.

neighborhood_overview: The Valley House is set amid woodland, lakes and hills, on the Northeast side of Achill Island.  You can drive on to the island via a bridge at Achill Sound, so access is easy and no ferries are necessary to get here.  We are approximately 10km from Achill Sound and about 8km from Keel.  You can cycle the wonderful Mayo Greenway, a scenic off-road cycling/walking trail.  The island offers a superb range of adventure sports on land, lake and sea as well as gorgeous walks in the magnificent Achill landscape.  Achill has 5 Blue Flag beaches and breathtaking scenery.

description:

neighborhood_overview:
Check out (URL HIDDEN)
This quaint fishing village has a welcoming community feel. With lots to do on the water including trips to the Islands, fishing and angling, boat tours, whale watching and diving. name: Donegal Cottage in lush countryside
description:
Donegal was voted the "Coolest place on the planet’ by National Geographic.

Our stone cottage is a restored farm building ( circa 1852 ), it is part of our home property, close to the main house. The restoration has a modern touch with tranquil decor. Our property is private and secluded.
The ancient Beltany Stone Circle is 5 minutes walk away and the historic village of
Raphoe 2kms away making this the ideal location from which to explore the magic of ‘Donegal’
neighborhood_overview:
We live in the rich pasturelands of east Donegal with rolling hills and patchwork field patterns. This is where you find our quaint heritage village , once a thriving market town with many of its 19th century buildings still adorning the centre. This was an ancient settlement probably before Christianity arrived. The nearby Beltany Stone Circle was an important pre-christian ritual site. Raphoe in gaelic is Rath Both , meaning the fort of the huts, either ancient dwellings or the holy huts of the monks. There was a monastery founded here by Eunan, the biographer of Colmcille , you will find the 9th century stone lintel of the monastery church in the vestibule of St. Eunan's Cathedral where the clock tower can been found. This historic building is worth a visit and dates back to 12th
century. Raphoe also has an imposing ruins of a 17th century castle built by Bishop Leslie, of the Church of Ireland. On the outskirts is Oakfield Park, once the Deanery to the Dioceses of
host_about: I am a former BBC journalist working across radio and television. I have a BA in History and Political Science and an MA in Landscape Archaeology. I enjoy traveling and I have lived and worked abroad in America, Japan, Belgium and London.  Among the countries I have visited  - S.Africa, Namibia, Egypt, Japan, Hong Kong, Australia, New Zealand, Turkey, America and much of Europe.   I hope I can help our guests appreciate all the delights that Donegal and our hinterland has to offer.

name: White cottage, real wood fire
description:
Enjoy privacy and comfort in your own handmade stone cottage, built 1830s, attached to our family home. 25mins drive from Kenmare. Private, self-contained, spacious, relaxed. Free fast wifi . Real wood fire. Comfy couch. Enjoy the beautiful Beara peninsula away from crowds, with lots to see nearby. Breakfast supplies provided. Basic cooking facilities.
Great local restaurants in the area, or book a homecooked welcome platter of local produce.
No late night check ins, this is a family home.
neighborhood_overview:
Lauragh offers breathtaking scenery in any weather. Mountains that change from green to grey to purple as the day progresses, lakes and rivers flowing to Kenmare Bay in fat torrents, and numerous woodlands.
Within a couple of miles there is a lovely coffee shop with bike rental, and a restaurant that is open all year round. Three miles away is Helen's Bar, a famous seaside pub where you can enjoy a pint and some food sitting on the pier. Go a little further afield and you have our nearest towns: Kenmare, to the east and Castletownbere to the west. Both have their own charms.

If you want to chill out on your holiday, we are in easy reach of the world famous Dzogchen Beara retreat centre. They offer free guided meditations twice a day, with the most amazing 180 degree view of the ocean. If that's not your thing, you can just have tea and cake in their lovely coffee shop and soak up the atmosphere.

There are loads of lovely drives from here - the Ring of Kerry
host_about: We live outside Kenmare, in the south west of Ireland. I work in adult literacy. My husband works in wildlife conservation. We live in a beautiful rural area, close to the sea, with two dogs, and an occasional cat who comes and goes as he pleases. We have two small boys aged 7 and 10. We love hillwalking, and exploring Killarney National Park (about an hour away). In the summer we like boating and sea fishing. We love music and film, and have an extensive dvd collection that's available for guests too.

neighborhood_overview:
The Dingle Peninsula can be reasonably considered as one of the most naturally beautiful places on earth. A finger of land stretching west, it features the Slieve Mish mountain range that forms its spine. Reaching 3123 feet above sea level rises Mount Brandon, the second highest mountain in Ireland. Falling sharply down to rolling green hills and farmland you will find our house nestled at the foot but still raised enough to view the spectacular scenery of the quaint villages, steep sea cliffs of the "Three Sisters" and the wild Atlantic beyond.

Centred on charming Dingle town, there's an alternative way of life here, lived by artisans and idiosyncratic characters and found at trad sessions and folkloric festivals across Dingle's tiny settlements.

name: The Red Stonecutters Cottage
description:
Red Stonecutters Cottage is perched atop stunning Doonagore, a short drive from Doolin village. From this high point, you'll enjoy views of the Atlantic Ocean, Aran Islands and the Burren. The cottage is a great base to enjoy the music in the Doolin pubs, beach in Lahinch and the harbour village of Liscannor.
The cottage dates back to after the famine and has been restored to preserve the original character, complemented by carefully selected period pieces to maintain its authentic charm.
neighborhood_overview:
The cottage is in a small terrace of four. The cottages were built for the stonecutters who lived in Doonagore. They were built during the days that the stone quarry was working (around 1850) and Doonagore was a busy village. There is very little left of the quarry workings now and the area is mostly dedicated to arable farming (There is an excellent exhibition in the Rock Shop in Liscanor that shows the history of the Doonagore quarry).

Although the cottage now sleeps two originally it would have been for a family of six or more (often including livestock).

Doonagore is on a height above the village of Doolin with roads that run to Lahinch and Liscannor.

There are fantastic views all around and great walking; all from the front door.
host_about:
After working for a number of years over-seas, we have recently retired and returned to Ireland. 

We own and manage a number of properties in the UK and Ireland – but we particularly enjoy restoring, refurbishing and modernizing 19th century authentic post-famine traditional  Irish cottages. 

We are also antique collectors, so we love finding and featuring Irish country antique furniture and photographs in our cottages. Sharing this authentic Irish experience is something we love to offer our guests.  

Because we ourselves  are nature  and animal lovers, and spend a lot of time hiking, cycling, golfing, surfing, bird-watching and dog-walking, we love living in Doolin.  

We are proud to offer you a delightful cozy Irish-cottage experience on a spectacular point in Doolin, that gives our guests panoramic views of the Atlantic, the Cliffs and the Aran Islands.  This is a magical place that will take you back in time……. cead mile failte! 

Phil and Val

neighborhood_overview:
Eden Retreat is located 4 miles north of the town of Ennis. Ennis gets its name from the Irish word “inis” (island) because it is virtually surrounded by the River Fergus, a melodious presence throughout. The streets of Ennis are narrow and charming, with many areas pedestrianized. There are plenty of locals here—Ennis is no tourist trap—and you’ll hear voices that are raised in laughter or storytelling in bakeries and bookstores alike. The Friary at the bottom of Abbey Street was founded by the O’Briens in the 13th century. Many of its original features survive. It’s breath-taking and has a textured silence that speaks through the centuries.

Why the Owner Chose Ennis:
The main attraction in Ennis is the locals’ love of traditional Irish music. The town is renowned as a hub of 'trad' music, and musicians of the highest quality are on display in the pubs of Ennis throughout the year. name: Atlantic Bay Rest bungalow - Dingle Peninsula
description: Welcome to Atlantic Bay Rest's authentic and rustic wooden bungalow right on the sea with private beach. Book it to stay at the edge of the world at one of the most beautiful spots on the Dingle Peninsula. If you are looking for a peaceful rest nestled in nature, this is it so please keep reading...
neighborhood_overview:
The property is located in the quiet village of Smerwick at the end of a tiny narrow country road. It's very calm and peaceful. The only traffic is when the farmers move their cows or sheep. Please always give way to cattle who don’t have a reverse gear.

If you somehow got tired of our private beach, you can walk 15 minutes to access another beautiful long beach, Beal Ban Beach. The historical "Fort Del Oro" is also a short walk from us, in the same direction as the beach.

For hikers, we are in a prime location to walk the 3 sisters and Mount Brandon with views over the ocean.

If you are a golfer and brought your golf clubs, an 18 hole golf links is only a 5 minutes drive away.

Ballyferriter village is also only a short drive away and has authentic pubs for a Guinness or some food.

There are no shops in Smerwick or Ballyferriter so if you'd like to use your kitchen, get your supplies in Dingle beforehand.
host_about:
Hi! I’m a Belgian who fell in love with Ireland. In 2020, I left Indonesia after a decade and started managing Atlantic Bay Rest from September 2022.

The founder, Peter from Germany, bought the property in the 70s. He still resides on the property. His son, Peter Paul, owns Atlantic Bay Rest but doesn’t reside at ABR.

Your booking supports a woman run / black owned business where all are welcome. The only thing required is a love for nature.

description: One of a handful of old thatched cottages still left in Donegal. This property nestles in a little hollow, in a peaceful rural setting with breathtaking surroundings and a lake and stunning beach within walking distance.
neighborhood_overview:
The Fanad Peninsula where the property is situated is an unspoilt scenic area with coastal drives, golden beaches, hedged country lanes and lakes and rivers. The area is good for fishing, golf, walking and relaxing.

There are numerous beaches within a 10 minute drive including Balllyhiernan surfers beach and surf school, Drumnacraig beach and Ballymastocker beach. Donegal is home to many Blue Flag beaches, so guests can rest easy in the knowledge that the water and sand are in pristine condition.

Fanad lighthouse is a signature point on the Wild Atlantic Way that overlooks the North Atlantic Ocean and only a 15 minute drive from the cottage. Other local attractions include Glenveagh Caste, Letterkenny, Rathmullan, Ramelton, Tory Island, Doe Castle, Downings, and Ards Forest Park which are all within a 45 minute drive.

name: The Old Hostel - Gortbee
description:
Mountain, Sky, Wind and Water - that's what you will experience at our cottage near the Hag's Glen and Carrauntoohil in County Kerry. A 20 minute drive from Killarney and at the centre of the Ring of Kerry in the heart of the McGillacuddy Reeks.

We now have excellent broadband in the cottage.
neighborhood_overview:
A 10 minute walk to Cronin's Yard - the most popular access route to the Carrauntoohil in the McGillacuddy Reaks (highest mountain in Ireland). The area is a hill walker's and mountaineer's paradise.

But the cottage is located just 20 minutes outside of Killarney where you have access to every facility from 5 star hotels to small bijou restaurants, tours, golf courses, horse racing, horse riding, kayaking, shopping and entertainment.

You can enjoy the remote solitude of the mountains or enjoy the food, shopping and entertainment of Killarney.

The cottage is ideally located for those wishing to drive the Ring of Kerry in one or more hops. Guests can also make wonderful day trips to Valentia Island, Skellig Islands, Dingle Peninsula, the Blasket Islands and North Cork.
host_about: I am a lecturer in the School of Electrical and Electronic Engineering at TU Dublin

name: Sunset by the Sea
description:
Three bed apartment.all mod cons..We offer a central location with spectacular views of the Cliffs of moher,Aran Islands,Seal island and Mutton Island all from the comfort of the garden! Close to family beaches restaurant's local pubs and traditional Irish music.
The accommodation suits groups and large families or if you just want a quiet space to reflect for a time and be surrounded by nature and peace and quiet,this is the perfect place for your stay.
Also suitable for wedding accommodation
neighborhood_overview:
A lovely town full of lovely people and steeped in traditional irish music.There are supermarkets to get your groceries, coffee shops,an ice cream shop and plenty of bars and Restaurants..All within easy access to the Cliffs of Moher,the Burren,Georges Head,the Bridges of Ross,Allawee Caves,Doolin Cave,Loophead,Doolin,Ballyvaughan and Kilfinora...All surfing and watersports are within a 5 to 10 minute drive from accomodation in Spanish Point(surfing)The White Strand(paddle boarding and kayaking) and Lahinch (#surf city)
Also perfect accomodation for local weddings.we are a 4 minute drive to Armada and Bellbridge Hotels
host_about:
My name is Shona. I am a singer songwriter living in Miltown Malbay. Music is a great passion for our family. My husband Paul is a classical guitarist and pianist. As well as teaching music he also finds time to accompany me and we perform locally and wherever the work takes us.
Paul is also an enthusiastic diver and we have plenty of local knowledge for anyone who would like to experience our beautiful coastline underwater!!!

As well as performing together Paul and I love walking and are more than happy to advise and recommend the beautiful walks our lovely county has to offer.
Finally we live on site and are available to answer any questions ,fix any problems or just give you space to enjoy your holiday..

name: Delux Two Bedroom Apartment 4 Star - Sleeps 4
description:
Burren Court Holiday Homes is a member of Burren EcoTourism. We are located 10 mins drive from the coastal village of Ballyvaughan, 20 minutes from the Cliffs of Moher and 30 mins drive from Doolin and ferry to Aran Islands.
Relax at Burren Court with family and enjoy guided walks, cycling, kayaking, surfing and visit Ailwee Cave and Doolin Cave. Bunratty Castle is 1 hour drive.
Shannon airport 1 hour and Galway City is 1 hour. Perfect base for exploring the Burren and Wild Atlantic Way
neighborhood_overview:
Burren Court is located in in the heart of the Burren, in a rural scenic area. It is a 10 minute drive to three vilages - Ballyvaughan, Kilfenora and Lisdoonvarna. There are very good cafes, pubs and restaurants in the local villages. It is less than half an hour to drive to visit the Cliffs of Moher, take a boat trip to the Aran Islands. Kayaking, rock climing and surfing are all within 15-20 minutes.
Walking and Cycling are on our doorstep, as we are on the Burren Way. Great beaches in this locality
host_about: We would love to welcome you to stay at Burren Court. With our love of the Burren and lots of  local knowledge, we do our best to ensure that our guests have a fantastic 'home from home' experience in Burren Court. We can recommend many things for guests to see and do

description: My home is cosy, warm and comfortable - looking out onto a park with children's playground. I have a bright and spacious sitting room leading into a kitchen/dining room. There are 2 bedrooms upstairs and full bathroom. Patio area and garden at rear
neighborhood_overview:
This is a quiet, safe, residential area with lots of local amenities within walking distance - supermarkets, pubs, and restaurants. The beautiful sea front at Clontarf is a five minute drive away and Dollymount strand and bird sanctuary just a minute or two further.

host_about:
I love living in Dublin almost as much as I love travelling.  Even after all these years I find that my home town still has loads to offer.
My favourite things are dining out, trying different cuisines and of course travelling to far flung destinations to sample the food there.  I love spending time with my 12 year old West highland Terrier - Puca (which is Irish for mischievous spirit).
I work as an accounts manager with a medical company - which is probably as boring as it sounds - hence the travelling!
As a guest I appreciate the opportunity to enjoy someone else's home and always treat the place with respect.  As a host I only ask you do the same.
I will do everything I can to make you feel welcome and to learn everything you need to know to enjoy our wonderful city.

name: Brennan's Old House, Loop Head
description: This 130 year old cottage, lovingly restored and full of character, retains its original stone finish - inside and out. Set on an acre of landscaped garden, it was the former home of Michael Brennan, a local blacksmith.
neighborhood_overview:
Brennan's Old House is situated on the lower road between the villages of Cross and Kilbaha; both are renowned for their restaurants, pubs and traditional music. A guide with our personal favourites and recommendations is kept in the cottage.

This headland is known as Loop Head. It is one of the most remote and beautiful places in the country, dividing the Shannon estuary from the open sea and is a Signature Point on the Wild Atlantic Way (the world's longest defined coastal touring route). It was designated Ireland's Aquatic Destination of Excellence in 2010 and was named the Irish Times 'Best Place to Holiday in Ireland' in their 2013 competition.

The lighthouse, at the point of Loop Head, is Clare's most westerly point with magnificent views of the Limerick and Kerry coastline, the Shannon and the Atlantic. It has stood guard there for over 340 years. Nearby, the Bridges of Ross are natural arches spanning the inlet of a natural harbour leading to the Atlantic
host_about: Although I'm from lovely rainy Ireland, I take every opportunity to explore other parts of the globe! Armed with my camera, I enjoy the path less travelled and living as a local. I try never to visit the same place twice but, every so often, Portugal, Croatia, Malta or Tasmania will draw me back!

name: The Lawn Yurt
description:
Welcome to The Old Forge Glamping. We have three yurts, a safari tent, a log cabin and a Shepherds Hut.

The Lawn Yurt looks out over the beautiful view of the Wicklow Mountains.

Our yurts come with linen supplied, access to a communal kitchen, a private campfire and bbq area. Each yurt has a double and 2 single beds.. The scenery is spectacular and it is a famous area for hill walking as it is located on the Wicklow Way walk.
neighborhood_overview: The rolling Wicklow Hills a spectacular to look out on especially Lungnaquilla Mountain.
host_about:
My husband and I set the business up 14 years ago and we have grown to now accommodate up to 40 people here on the farm. We really enjoy sharing this beautiful place with like minded nature lovers. The Old Forge Glamping sleeps 22 and the Granary and 10 House sleep 6 and 8 respectively.  
Sitting around a campfire on a beautiful summer evening is one of the greatest things one can do, it's totally relaxing and we love meeting people.

name: Artistic Cottage Retreat Connemara - An Muileann
description:
Escape to An Muileann, a charming blend of modern comfort and traditional Irish cottage nestled in the heart of Kilkieran, a picturesque village along Ireland's famed Wild Atlantic Way. Located in the unspoiled beauty of Connemara, An Muileann offers an unforgettable retreat where you can truly unwind and immerse yourself in serene surroundings.​

Immerse yourself in the Irish language and culture, as Kilkieran is part of the Gaeltacht region, where Irish is the predominant language.
neighborhood_overview:
We are situated on the west coast of Ireland, on the wild Atlantic way, one of the most beautiful, unspoilt places you can find in the world

Only 2 minutes drive from Kilkieran village where you will find a supermarket, pub, bistro & post office. Kids newly built playground is only a short walk away. Carna village a 10 minute drive away which has a petrol station, pharmacy, post office, restaurant/pub Mac's (Tigh Mheaic) and Moran's pub.

From the rugged Twelve Bens mountain range in the north through lake-rich Roundstone Bog to the nearby golden beaches reaching out into the Atlantic Ocean, you'll know you're in Connemara by the light that constantly changes the mood and tone of the landscape.

The natural terrain and unspoilt environment offer the visitor a wonderland of sights, experiences, adventure and activities. The people are warm, friendly and extend a hospitality which is the essence of Connemara.

Enjoy some of the most spectacular
host_about:
Dia dhuit! Hello! We are a local family who love offering our home to Airbnb guests so that they can truely enjoy all that this beautiful region has to offer.  

We love to host guests and share our knowledge of the local area, traditional music and Irish folkore.  
If you are interested in knowing more along this line, we would be more than happy to share it!

We have a keen interest in the arts and enjoy learning about other cultures, traditions, languages and history. 

Gaeilge agus fáilte
We are Irish (Gaelic) speakers

name: Country Living at The Potter's Yard
description: Artist's stable conversion in rural South Wexford. High ceilings. Large en suite double bedroom.  Fully fitted kitchen. Wi-Fi.  Secure off-road parking. Patio & private orchard.  Pub five minutes' walk. Beach & shops five minutes' drive. Pop-up pottery workshops available by prior arrangement at an agreed fee.
neighborhood_overview: The Potter's Yard is an off-road traditional South Wexford stone-built dormer farmhouse with adjacent stone outbuildings, including the Airbnb apartment and  a pottery studio and shop, surrounded by a paddock, orchard, and large pasture. Farmland nearby is devoted to dairy farming. As noted in a previous guest review we are close to a number of nature reserves and bird sanctuaries. The apartment can accommodate two more people prepared to share the sofa bed - useful for people engaged in orienteering, etc. given prior notice and mutual agreement.
host_about: I am a social historian and published author, with three grown children, living with my spouse Patricia who is a potter. My love of travel goes back to my days 'on the road' in Europe in the 'Sixties. I am a graduate of two UK universities, a lover of folk music, storytelling (not myths & legends) cats, and the Guardian newspaper.

name: Rathmines Apt 2
description:
This a 1 bedroom apartment located on the first floor of the Upper Rathmines area.



It is next to a lovely array of shops including a Tescos, a fresh veg shop, a butcher's, a fishmonger, and a hairdressers.

This is a residential area and suits first time visitors.

Getting to the City Center: Stephen's Green.
Approximately 3km from the propery.

Walking: A 36 minute walk.
Car: An 11 minute drive.
Public transport (The Luas tram system): 26 minutes on the tram system.
neighborhood_overview:
The Rathmines/Rathgar area is extremely peaceful, just fifteen minutes away from the city via the Luas, you are close to the heart of the city but without the noise or hustle and bustle.
Along the street, there is a butchers, fishmongers, fresh fruit and vegetable shop, a bakers, a chemist, and a convenience store so everything is within your reach.
Just a ten minute walk into Lower Rathmines will bring you to an array of restaurants and bars.
host_about:
As a host, I like to leave my guests to do their own thing, I'm there whenever they need me but I want their apartment to feel like their space- not like they're renting a room. 
In return, all I ask is that guests communicate with me and have a great time.

name: Coastal Paradise in West Cork
description: This old coastguard house has been completely refitted in the last few years and offers a unique opportunity to get away from it all and reconnect with nature in the idyllic setting of beautiful Glandore. Unobstructed Ocean views on your front door and access to the sea from the garden.
neighborhood_overview: Glandore must be one of the most beautiful villages anywheres in the world. It sits quite high looking onto a 3km inlet off the Atlantic Ocean. As a result you really get a panoramic viewpoint of the water and all activities on it. Glandore harbour is guarded by two islands called Adam and Eve, the old sailors mantra goes 'avoid Adam and hug Eve'. There are two castles (privately owned) one 3000 year old stone circle, 3 great pubs, 2 lovely restaurants, wonderful scenic walks and some truly wonderful people. What more could you want really.
host_about:
Professional relaxed guy. Work in the more creative fields. 
Enjoy the adventure of life. An eclectic taste in music. Enjoy reading from cheesy to psychology stuff. Moviewise am a big Coen brothers and Wes Anderson fan. Enjoy meeting new people and equally enjoy time to myself. Quite active and enjoy alot of board sports - snowboarding, wakeboarding, long boarding etc.

* You can walk from the house to the beach (a wild, untamed, beautiful beach) in about 10 minutes...

* If you walk along the beach to the right you will come to the mouth of the Boyne River, where it meets the sea. The river is the main artery of the whole Boyne Valley (and it's also apparently great for fishing)....

name: Cowper 415
description:
Welcome to this modern apartment situated in the charming Upper Rathmines neighborhood.
We provide essential amenities such as linens, towels, and shower gel.

Nestled in a residential area, this location offers a tranquil retreat while remaining close to key attractions.

Conveniently positioned just 3km from the City Center (Stephen's Green), accessibility is straightforward:
- Walking Distance: 41 minutes
- Driving: 12 minutes
- Public Transport (The Luas Tram service): 19 minutes
neighborhood_overview:
Rathmines (Irish: Ráth Maonais, meaning 'ringfort of Maonas') is an inner suburb on the Southside of Dublin in Ireland.
It lies three kilometres south of the city centre. It begins at the southern side of the Grand Canal and stretches along the Rathmines Road as far as Rathgar to the south, Ranelagh to the east, and Harold's Cross to the west.
It is situated in the city's D06 postal district.

Rathmines is served by the Luas light rail system: Ranelagh on the Green Line is the most convenient for access to the main street, while the Charlemont and Beechwood stops are also within walking distance of the area.

Dublin Bus routes 14, 15, 15A, 15B, 18, 65, 65B, 83, 140 and 142 serve Rathmines. The area is also served by the Dublin Bus Nitelink routes 15N and 49N on Friday and Saturday nights and on public holidays.
host_about:
As a host, I like to leave my guests to do their own thing, I'm there whenever they need me but I want their apartment to feel like their space- not like they're renting a room. 
In return, all I ask is that guests communicate with me and have a great time.

name: Rathfarnham Large Room
description:
We are a married couple in our 60’s with a jack russell dog, called Mimi.

We have a cosy home in Rathfarnham, south of the city, a 25-35 min journey to the city served by 2 good bus services.

The Dublin mountains are 10 minutes drive away. We have 3 local parks nearby, a Castle in our own local Rathfarnham Castle Park, a village and Dundrum town centre for shopping.
neighborhood_overview: We live at the end of a quiet cul de sac.  There is lovely interaction in the evenings with the children outside playing.  A walk into Rathfarnham Castle Park with the beautiful castle and pond is enjoyable. You can get to one bus stop via the park and village. The ducks can be fed if you like.  The village is so close, you won't be short of anything.  There are 3 pubs, serving food, a small supermarket,  bank machines, a post office, take-aways and restaurants.
host_about:
We are a couple in our early 60’s living in a quiet cul de sac close to Rathfarnham village. We are 3 minutes walk away from bus stops, our village, a beautiful park, a castle, and 10 minute drive to the Dublin mountains and approx 25 minute bus ride to the city centre.

We have been hosting guests and international students in our home for the last 7 years, so we love to welcome new people visiting Dublin.  We like music, particularly the Ukulele, books, and cooking.  Our garden has many herbs, flowers and vegetables growing this season.  Our motto in life is "keep it simple".

neighborhood_overview:
The cottage is situated in Knightstown village, so ideally located for walking to a variety of local pubs and restaurants. The harbour and marina are a short stroll away.
Being a spectacular unspoilt island, the most westerly inhabited island in Europe, it is a place of natural beauty.. Our locality offers the guests experiences such as swimming in crystal clear water, boat trips to a deserted island, cycling along the byroads, playing tennis, fishing, kayaking, sailing, diving,walking, hiking the cliffs, rock pooling on the local beach, sub tropical gardens, ancient healing wells, scenic viewing points, dinasaur footprints, lighthouse tours, candle making, horse carriage tours and local chocolates. Star gazing is becoming increasingly popular as we have been designated as part of the darkest skies in the Northern Hemisphere. Boat trips to the UNESCO world heritage site of the Skellig islands, can be arranged. On The Wild Atlantic Way and part of the 10 best places to visit acc

name: Tír Conaill
description:
Tír Conaill is a family run business nestled in Adare, Ireland’s prettiest village. Thatched roof cottages, tudor style houses, beautiful gardens and ivy clad medieval churches all set on the River Maigue makes Adare a must see when visiting Ireland.

Tír Conaill is the perfect place to stay when visiting the South West of Ireland and the award winning Wild Atlantic Way. Adare is the centre point when visiting Dingle, Killarney, the Rock of Cashel, Blarney Stone and world famous Cliffs of Moher.
neighborhood_overview: Adare (Áth Dara) meaning 'ford of the oak' is a village nestled in the south west of Ireland and is regarded as being Ireland's prettiest and most picturesque village. Adare is a haven for those wanting to escape and unwind taking in its medieval surroundings. Situated on the river Maigue, a tributary of the river Shannon, Adare is steeped in history dating back to 1200 ad. Adare has been the subject of many rebellions, wars and conquests, leaving behind a legacy of historical monuments. In the early 19th century, the Earl of Desmond, laid the plan for the existing streets and townhouses of Adare. These lands and dwellings were rented to tenants, under various agreements, some of which still exist today.  A walk through Adare is a must for all visitors.
host_about:
I have been running my B&B for the past 20 years and enjoy meeting, greeting and talking to people from all parts of the world. I hope to assist guests in having a wonderful holiday in Ireland with advice and tips on visiting all the gems of Ireland. Céad míle fáilte.

name: The Studio at The Bastion
description: The Studio at The Bastion is a self contained unit. Its right across the road from the main house. Free WiFi available.  Help yourself to fresh tea & coffee. Breakfast is not included but it's available right next door at The Bastion Kitchen. Private bathroom. Kitchenette with sink and small fridge, toaster and kettle. Cable TV.
host_about:
Hi there! We’re brothers Anthony & Vinny McCay and  we run The Bastion. Our street is named after the Royal Bastion which once occupied the street where we are.

 Our house is a bit of a labyrinth inside. There's lots of history here. The world famous Irish tenor John Count McCormack often visited in the early 1900s.  Our great great grandfather Michael Kilkelly was his first tutor.

Our style is laid back and relaxed. We love good food and the left bank area  is a gourmet district with lots of great restaurants and pubs. You definitely won't go hungry here.  Ireland's Oldest Bar is just down the hill. There is music most evenings. 

The beautiful river Shannon is just at the end of the street. The imposing and enormous stone castle built by King John in 1210 majestically guards the river crossing. 

In 1691 the area was besieged by the armies of King William of Orange in a battle with King James for the English throne.  Twelve thousand cannon balls were fired across the river in the barrage that ensued. We have one of them!

The nearby  Luan Gallery hosts great exhibitions throughout the year.

name: Sunlit Guinness House Beside the Phoenix Park.
description:
Internally, a modern refurbished gem that is airy, bright & equipped with everything for your stay in Dublin's fair city. Externally, a Victorian artisan house in a friendly safe neighborhood built for Guinness Brewery workers back in 1890!

Parking in front or at the side of the property is free. City Centre is a 30 minute walk. A city bus stop is right in front of the house. It's a 10 minute walk the LUAS (city light rail system) & Heuston train station, to Galway, Cork, Kerry and Belfast.
neighborhood_overview:
This cosmopolitan neighbourhood is perfect if you want to be within minutes of the best that Dublin has to offer, but without the noise and hustle and bustle.

Sullivan street was one of the first developments by the Guinness family to provide housing for employees in the 1890's. It's the archetypal Dublin red brick terrace that is very central and alive with city living.

Phoenix Park – the largest in-city park in the world – is literally on your doorstep, and is also home to Dublin Zoo. Dublin’s biggest tourist attraction – the Guinness Storehouse – is a few minutes walk, as well as other big names such as the Jameson Distillery, the Irish Museum of Modern Art and the Four Courts.
host_about:
Hello! You are very welcome.

Your hosts: James, Megan and 2 busy kids are happy to facilitate your stay and help you explore the area. 

We lived in the brick Dublin house from 2004-2014. Before moving in, we reinvented the interior of the house to create a bright open space with a total remodel. We love our first home here in this truly unique award winning North Dublin neighbourhood. This property is now rented full-time.

The blue Victorian house is our family home in Boise, Idaho in another wonderfully appreciated historic neighborhood (USA now, proper spellings). We are walking distance from downtown in the city's East End. The quiet apartment is above our family home. It has a seperate entrance and all the amenities required for a comfortable stay. It’s been updated and set up for short term contract professionals - but we host tourists too. This location is ideal. 

The Cheerful Cottage is located in central Nampa, Idaho and James worked hard during 2021 to bring this previously neglected property some new life.  In July 2022 it became ready for you to enjoy.  An adorable 1 bedroom property with a fenced shady yard and relaxing patio bordered by a single car garage. A bright quiet space with everything you need for a short or long term visit. 

Megan is a Musician and Music Teacher. James, an Artist, a Designer, a Director and Research Manager. The kids are not ready to settle on a profession just yet other than as students (in school and of the world).
We love to travel and spend time with with friends and family.

neighborhood_overview:
We love our apartment because of it's central location in the heart of "auld" Dublin where everything is accessible on foot. Experience all that Dublin has to offer from lively pubs and restaurants to a vibrant cultural scene and beautifully manicured urban parks.

From the apt you will have panoramic views of the old city walls of Dublin and the Liberties. You will be 2 mins walk away from Christchurch Cathedral and cultural quarter Temple Bar. The Guinness Storehouse and Jameson Distillery are within throwing distance as are all major transport systems including the Luas (2 mins), the DART and various bus and rail services such you wish to explore further afield. A trip to the seaside village of Howth perhaps?

host_about:
Brazilian-Irish married couple with 3 kiddies who are passionate about travel, food (+ wine) and music! When we visit other cities around the world we love to live like the locals and try to seek out a "fixer" who can tell us what's what and where are the best places to go.  We want to be the Dublin fixers for our guests when they come and stay. We work both in the wine and events industry in Ireland and we like to think that we are part of the fabric of Dublin. Yasmine is an avid shopper passionate about hospitality and Colin loves nothing more than to disappear up the mountains around Dublin on his bike. 

The appeal of airbnb to us is that we get to meet and interact with like minded people who are willing to share a piece of themselves with others, and to experience a different view on what could otherwise be an ordinary one!

name: Georgian charm near Lough Corrib and Connemara
description: Carrownacroagh House is a listed eighteenth century country house in quiet rural North Galway. It was built by the Skerrett family, one of the renowned Tribes of Galway. The house has been carefully restored by us, offering a unique opportunity to enjoy an historic building in sequestered comfort. The village of Headford is ten minutes' drive,  the vibrant city of Galway thirty, and the stunning scenery of Connemara an hour away. The secluded location means a car is essential.
neighborhood_overview: This part of Co Galway is quiet and unspoilt. It is a mecca for both antiquarian and angler. Lough Corrib is a short stroll away, and several quiet inlets and small harbours with launching ramps are nearby. The medieval attractions of Ross Errilly Friary - one of the finest monastic sites in Ireland - are just five minutes drive away, and another minute brings you to the village of Headford, with supermarket, hotel and several pubs and restaurants. The charming village of Cong is 20 mins drive, and many other fine ancient sites are nearby. The scenic splendours of Connemara are 40 mins drive, and the vibrant city of Galway just 30 mins away.
host_about: Professional musician, originally from New Zealand, living and working in Ireland since 1992. Since 2003 my husband Tom and I have been living in a large Georgian farmhouse in North Galway, and enjoying the slow process of renovation and restoration. We're delighted now to be sharing it with others via  Airbnb. We are both keen cooks and gardeners, and also enjoy travelling to Crete where we have a small farmhouse in the south-west.

name: CROWS' HERMITAGE
description: A Romantic Retreat -Tastefully converted stone barn with views of 13th C. Abbey ruins & mature garden. Ideal location for touring east coast and Dublin (Airport 30min). Mezzanine bedroom overlooking the open plan living area & wood burning stove.
neighborhood_overview:
Ardcath is a tiny, quiet village in County Meath, near the border to County Dublin. The village pub is a three minute walk away and is full of character. It hosts an informal traditional Irish music session every Thursday night and guests are welcome, even encouraged, to play or sing. The musicians will even provide you with a musical instrument!
Convenience stores are a 5 minute drive. A selection of restaurants in nearby villages - Kilmoon (4 miles), Stamullen (5 miles), Duleek (4 miles) - and in the local large town of Drogheda (10 miles) provide a wide range of menus to suit all tastes.

This is an excellent location for touring both Dublin city (50mins drive) and the east coast. The Boyne Valley, Newgrange heritage site and the Hill of Tara are within 20mins drive, as are the beaches of Bettystown and Gormanston. Enjoy any one of a dozen excellent golf courses within 20 miles, as well as horse racing at nearby Bellewstown, Fairyhouse or on the strand at Laytow
host_about: Hi, my name is Colm. I am originally from nearby Drogheda but have been living in Ardcath for more than thirty years. I converted the barn in 2008 and I enjoy welcoming guests from all over the world to stay here. I hope to make you feel welcome and give any advice and information I can to make your stay as enjoyable as possible.

The loveliest aspect to living in Moynalty is the friendly people who are so proud of their Village. The old Village was erected in 1860 and you will see how beautifully maintained these homes are.
There is a beautiful park in the village which is also home to a local museum.
host_about:
I moved to Moynalty in recent years.  Here I have found a wonderful community, a beautiful environment and a vastly rich heritage.
My hobbies include horticulture,  cycling and minding a little flock of Rhode Island Hens who live with Roosty and Carmella, a rescued cockeral and hen  (Light Sussex and Buff Orpington) Bluebell hens arrived Summer 2016.   Recently Black Orpington hens arrived.  Babooshka a lively Tibetan Terrier (from DSPCA)  lives here  and Tom a wild cat provide security.  Four other cats live here.  June, Natalie Blacky and Dicky.  All showed up liked what they saw and moved in.   

I enjoy welcoming guests to experience the proverbial natural beauty of Moynalty and meet my neighbours.

name: 2bed Dingle central location
description: 2 bed cottage nestled in a quiet cosy corner, 2 minutes walk to explore the magic of Dingle. Suitable for children over 12 years only. Parking one car guaranteed. No smoking or vaping in or around the property.
neighborhood_overview:
Dingle is much loved for the pretty colourful townhouses that create a backdrop for its lively marina. It offers a wide variety of restaurants but it's the quaint pubs that are a must on the to-do list. Some are truly original, full of character and 'characters'. Real Irish music and real Irish craic not to be missed!

Awarded 'Best Foodie Town in Ireland 2014' Dingle has a wide variety of restaurants to suit all tastes.

Explore Dingle's craft shops and artisan workshops. You will find local pottery, luxury handbags,woollens soaps and candles. You may trip upon the weaver at work,order a specially designed piece of jewellery or purchase some local artwork to remind you of your visit.
Dingle boasts a specialty cheese shop that is well worth a visit. Locally crafted beer and Dingle gin should also be sampled.
For those who prefer the outdoors Dingle Penninsula has ancient dwellings, winding stone walls and panoramic views of the wild Atlantic.

,30minutes by car on the m1 motorway to Dublin Airport . All guest can be at Newgrange / bru na Boinne visitor centre for the first tour at 9 ,30 We are only 6k by car. We live in the countryside with lots of walks by the river Boyne. or across the fields.
