host_about:
Bru na Boinn/ Newgrange visitor center is 6k from our front door . Come stay with us and share in the magic of the Valley of Kings. Our family has lived in the co Meath area for over 200 years. Our two storey country home is built on the site of the famous Battle of the Boyne. Ideal location for touring Ireland's  east coast.  angling in many local rivers and touring the megalithic tombs of Newgrange, Nowth,Dowth.Also Hill of Tara (seat of the King’s of Ireland),Medieval monastery and the historic town of Drogheda. Nature walks begin at our front door in any direction, one of which brings you to the boyne canal boardwalk only 50 meters down the road. The Oldbridge Parkrun  uses these tracks every Saturday morning at 9:30.

Take a journey back in time with our:
Currach ride’s (our traditional irish boats) 
Horse trekking/carriage ride’s (on our irish cob’s)
By arrangement (extra charge)

My name is Arthur I  would like to invite you to join my family,, around our table to share tales of local history and your travel experiences.

name: Comfortable Apartment onFamily Organic Apple Farm.
neighborhood_overview:
Kilkenny City is a medieval city and is home to Ireland's crafts industries and many famous festivals including Rhythm and Roots Weekend, (May Bank Holiday), The Cat Laugh Comedy Festival, (June Bank Holiday), Thomastown Traditional Irish Music weekend (August Bank Holiday) Kilkenny Arts Festival (August) Kilkenomics - the world's first festival of economics and comedy (5th - 9th of November) and Subtitle Film Festival (23rd - 29th of Nov).

Some of Ireland's finest studio workshops are located in Kilkenny. The Craft Trail is perhaps the best way to sample each artist, which are easily found in Kilkenny City, Bennettsbridge, Thomastown and Inistioge. We have information leaflets available at Highbank Orchards.

Kilkenny is also famous for it's artisan food. The best way to experience this is to follow the food trail where you can visit award winning chocolatiers, cheese makers, trout farms and of course ourselves! We have leaflets available one the Kilkenny food tra
host_about: I am a teacher and a farmer, living and working on our organic apple farm and distillery for over 33 years. Our family have lived at Highbank for five generations.

neighborhood_overview:
Our home stands on a large site surrounded by farmland in Clonmany on the Inishowen Peninsula, where there is something for all ages and interests. A short walk along the riverside leads you to Clonmany village where the Clonmany Festival, Ireland's longest running and best known family festival takes place between the 2nd-9th August 2015. This is where crowds gather for open air concerts,live music,fun and activities.
Inishowen has a lot to offer, from Malin Head, Ireland's most northerly point to the remote and very beautiful Mamore Gap. It also boasts award winning beaches and restaurants, great fishing, the famous Ballyliffin golf course, cosy traditional pubs ,where you can enjoy a pint of Guinness and music sessions by the fire.
The spectacular Glenevin Waterfall and picnic areas lie only 2 kilometers from Clonmany village.
For those with a love of history, no visit is complete without a trip to Clonmany's Famine Village.

If you drive, 5 minutes' further walking down a grassy lane is required to reach this nearest beach.

name: Rustic holiday cottage near Bantry
description: Restored Irish Cottage and Barn with stunning views over the valley and hills, just outside of Bantry. You'll find Glanatnaw tucked away up a private drive way in a secluded and peaceful spot. Sleeps 8 in four bedrooms. Idyllic getaway.
neighborhood_overview:
The surrounding area

Bantry and the surrounding area is located in County Cork one of Ireland's most beautiful counties, offering coastline, hills, colourful market towns, celebrated local produce, and plenty of good pubs. There are a host of cafes and restaurants that pride themselves in sourcing local produce.

Glanathnaw is a short distance from the bustling market town of Bantry, and within easy reach of a host of other delightful coastal towns: Skibbereen, Ballydehob, Baltimore and Schull. It is also close to the wild coastlines of Mizen Head and Sheeps Head which has a network of footpaths to explore.

Things to do

There are plenty of things to do in the surrounding area. Some of the highlights are:

• Beaches: Some favourites are Barley Cove, Akahista & Toormoore
• Walks: A huge variety of coastal & river walks
• Sailing at Schull and Baltimore
• Superb salmon fishing on the nearby Bandon and Owvane

description: Crag Shore is located a short distance from Lahinch (Lehinch) on the (N67). The Wild Atlantic Way. We're  on the southern side of Lahinch (Lehinch). neighborhood_overview:
Lahinch is acclaimed for the top quality surfing conditions available offshore. Indeed the Guinness record for number of surfers on a wave is held by Lahinch. Surf lessons and equipment for hire as available in the village. Other water sports including kitesurfing and windsurfing are catered for as well. The pitch-in-putt course is two kilometers outside the town on the road to Liscannor.

All-weather facilities at the seaside resort include an aquarium and indoor pool close to the fine beachside promenade. Lahinch has many fantastic shops, offering gifts from Ireland, including Waterford crystal, knitwear, jewellery, golf attire, belleek and pottery, an art gallery and Cuban cigar shop!
